<HEAD>Ethiopian Guerrillas Claim Capture of Three Strategic Towns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH ZARROUG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ethiopian guerrillas on Thursday claimed they captured three garrison towns in northern <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, including <LOCATION> Korem </LOCATION>, the site of a major government food relief station in the drought-stricken region. The towns were taken Wednesday, according to <PERSON> Yemane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kidane </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Tigrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> official. He said nothing of casualties. <PERSON> Yemane </PERSON> said a joint force of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> and the newly formed <ORGANIZATION> Ethiopian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> took <LOCATION> Korem </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Wollo </LOCATION> province, while <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> forces simultaneously captured the garrison towns of <LOCATION> Amba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alage </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kasad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gudu </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Tigre </LOCATION> province, <LOCATION> Wollo </LOCATION>'s northern neighbor. The inaccessibility of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s northern region makes independent verification of government or rebel claims difficult. In <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s capital, <PERSON> Addis </PERSON> <PERSON> Ababa </PERSON>, government spokesman <PERSON> Teklu </PERSON> <PERSON> Tabor </PERSON> refused to comment. Western sources said they had heard no reports of any of the towns falling. Widespread crop failures last year have left 1 million people in need of emergency food aid in <LOCATION> Wollo </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Korem </LOCATION>, 250 miles north of <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>, has been a major government food distribution station. Government relief workers there have been handing out one-month rations to about 6,000 people a day. Fighting in <LOCATION> Tigre </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s northernmost province, <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>, has crippled relief operations aimed at feeding an estimated 3.2 million drought victims in those provinces. There are 7 million drought victims nationwide. <PERSON> Yemane </PERSON> said the rebel operation was aimed at thwarting a big offensive President <PERSON> Mengistu </PERSON> <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Mariam </PERSON> is preparing for Tigre. The push started in <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> and stalled, said <PERSON> Yemane </PERSON>, repeating claims made by the <ORGANIZATION> Eritrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. The secessionist <ORGANIZATION> Eritrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> has been fighting for 27 years in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s longest civil war. The <ORGANIZATION> Tigrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> took up arms against the <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION> government in 1974 demanding greater autonomy. <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> inherited the insurgencies 14 years ago when he, with a group of army officers, overthrew Emperor <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Selassie </PERSON>. The government and the two rebel fronts all are Marxist. <PERSON> Yemane </PERSON> rejected Zambian President <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaunda </PERSON>'s plea at the summit in <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION> of the Organization of African Unity that the rebels make peace with the government. `` There will be no peace in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> unless <LOCATION> Mengistu </LOCATION> is destroyed,'' <PERSON> Yemane </PERSON> said.
