<HEAD>Report: Bush, Meese Met Secretly To Discuss AG's Legal Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> met privately with Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> recently to discuss political ramifications of the attorney general's ongoing legal problems, according to a published report. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, citing unidentified sources in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is vacationing, reported in Saturday editions that the secret meeting took place at <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s request shortly before May 16 The newspaper said it could not be learned what <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had told <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>. Two <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aides earlier this month called <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> a campaign liability, but the vice president denied he had authorized the statements. In the past, the vice president has declined to comment on whether the embattled attorney general should step down, claiming he did n't want to prejudge the case. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s financial dealings in several areas are under investigation by independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>, who is expected to issue a report in several weeks raising questions about <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s ethical conduct. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>, contacted in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION> about the Post story, said: `` We have no comment on that.'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said he conferred with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> chief of staff <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, who decided that the campaign should not respond to the story.
