<FIRST>r a PM-TurtleRepair     05-27 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turtle Repair,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veterinarian Uses Auto-Body Resin, Fiberglass To Patch Up Snapping
Turtle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A veterinarian who used auto-body resin and fiberglass cloth to patch up a wounded snapping turtle says his 22-pound patient is `` crawling around nicely.'' A woman who found the turtle in a pool of blood off Route 28 corralled it into a box and brought it to <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Messenger </PERSON>. The snapper had been hit by a car on the highway, and by the time it got to Messenger, it had lost a lot of blood and chunks of its shell were missing. Despite Messenger's experience with exotic animals _ including a cobra from which he removed a mouth tumor _ he had never worked on a snapper before, let alone a 20-year-old equipped with jaws that could nip off a finger. `` It was very challenging,'' the veterinarian said Thursday. After cleaning out the wound and covering it with gauze, Messenger injected antibiotics into the turtle's tail to fend off infection. Then he let the turtle rest for a couple days before operating on Wednesday. After trimming away dead and damaged tissue, and using a saw to cut off damaged bone and shell, Messenger used auto-body repair resin and fiberglass cloth to repair the damaged shell. `` The prognosis is very good,'' Messenger said Thursday. `` He's crawling around nicely. Messenger said he will keep the turtle for a couple of weeks to watch its recovery, then let it loose near to where it was found. Meantime, he said, he will have to find food for it. `` I think I'm going to go out fishing,'' he said.
</TEXT>
