<FIRST>r i PM-Panama-Repression     05-27 0843</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Repression,0870</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noriega Regime Intimidates Opposition With Beatings, Threats</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The regime of Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has used detentions, beatings, threats and sexual harassment to intimidate Panamanians and quell what appeared only a month ago to be a rising wave of protest. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> does n't have to resort to slayings or to arranging for people to `` disappear,'' as has happened in some Latin American dictatorships. Panamanians themselves are the first to admit they are unaccustomed to violent abuse and are easily cowed by it. `` I took part in demonstrations until they detained me,'' said a 27-year-old lawyer, who asked not to be named for fear of reprisals. She was released after a half hour, but not before being insulted, threatened and fondled by policemen. `` We are not <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. We do n't have violence in our blood,'' said <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Romero </PERSON>, secretary-general of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Romero </PERSON> was detained, interrogated and beaten May 5 when he returned from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where he had gone to take part in a conference. He was expelled to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> the next day and allowed to return on Monday. `` There is a triumph of terror,'' he told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in an interview. `` The regime is waging psychological war, and it's winning. The Defense Forces, which includes police and armed forces and is under <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s command, did not return repeated telephone calls Thursday asking for a response to these allegations. Only three people have been killed in political violence since the U.S.-backed opposition campaign to oust <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> began 11 months ago. There are no `` disappeared,'' the enigmatic status that military regimes in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> conferred on tens of thousands of opponents in past decades. But there is a secret police, G-2, whose members have demonstrated ruthlessness. The corps is informed by street spies called `` toads'' whose pervasive infiltration of everyday life is taken for granted. `` We're not fighters, but a folkloric people; beach, sun and sea,'' said a young professional jailed and mistreated for a week last month. `` I myself am that way. It's in our genes.'' The man said he was suspected of opposition activity and taken from his home after midnight by several agents to G-2 headquarters. He was stripped and his wrists handcuffed behind his back. Asthmatic and frail, he was forced to stand under a cold shower for half an hour, punched in the face and abdomen and beaten on the legs with a rubber hose, he reported. Then he was beaten on the toes with a blackjack, a pain he describes as `` terrible.'' Still nude and handcuffed, as he was to remain for 15 hours, he was thrown into a cell where he was told he would be raped by an inmate. Panamanian rights activists say a sexual element to physical or psychological abuse of detainees is common. They report that arrested people are frequently threatened with rape or sodomy. The young man was not sexually abused, he said. But when he was taken from the cell several hours later, he was blindfolded, his mustache was burned with a lighter and the barrel of a revolver was placed at his temple. `` They told me the cemetery was just down the road,'' he said. `` My life is the university, work and my girlfried,'' said the man, who fears reprisal if his name appears in print. `` Those seven days were like a parenthesis, a long nightmare.'' `` The day after I got out, there was a -LRB- anti-government -RRB- march. I did not even think about going,'' he said. `` Our security forces are more clever than the Argentines -LRB- of the 1970s -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Weeden </PERSON>, a lawyer who in the past year has represented dozens of people arrested on political charges. `` Fear is stronger than cadavers. People get used to cadavers, but they do n't get used to fear.'' He said that since a failed coup attempt in March, the prevailing paranoia has spread to the Defense Forces. He said the 18 officers and soldiers under arrest in connection with the attempt have been subjected to treatment as least as humiliating as that given civilians. `` The officers know that if they cast a funny glance at <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> or one of his inner circle, they will be under surveillance themselves,'' said <PERSON> Weeden </PERSON>. `` There's even more fear inside the armed forces than outside,'' he said. Except for the coup plotters, political detainees are rarely held more than a few days or a week. Most are required to pay between $ 150 and $ 350 for their freedom, though payments of up to $ 10,000 have been reported. Opposition leaders and human rights activists call the payments `` ransoms.'' Weeden thinks the lull in protest and street demonstrations is passing, a valley to be followed by a surge. <PERSON> Romero </PERSON> said he came back to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> even though his wife pleaded with him by telephone not to. `` I'm showing my face and going ahead to help smash the terror,'' he said.
</TEXT>
