<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal officials plan to sue <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> for violating the voting rights of racial minorities by diluting their influence when county supervisors redrew district boundaries in 1981, a source said Thursday. Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> informed the county by letter last week that he authorized the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to sue the county for allegedly discriminating against minorities in the 1981 reapportionment, said the source, who is familiar with the case but asked not to be identified. The Board of Supervisors must remap its five districts every decade and to divide the population evenly among them. But the 1981 plan allegedly diluted the influence of Hispanics and other minorities, the source added. County Counsel <PERSON> DeWitt </PERSON> <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> was called for comment Thursday, but did n't immediately return the call. There has not been a Hispanic supervisor in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s 138-year history The county's only black supervisor, <PERSON> Yvonne </PERSON> <PERSON> Brathwaite </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, was appointed to the board in the 1970s and subsequently lost a bid for election. According to the 1980 federal census, there were more than 2 million Hispanics and 943,000 blacks among the county's 7.5 million residents. By 1985 there were 2.4 million Hispanics and 964,000 blacks, according to projections by the county <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Burstion-Wade </PERSON> confirmed <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s civil rights division, sent a letter to the county last week, but said she could n't comment on its contents In voting rights cases, such letters are sent to allow the target of a potential lawsuit to negotiate with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and `` avoid the cost and time of litigation, which does n't help anybody,'' she said by phone from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` However, if statutory violations can not be resolved, then certainly litigation is a real possibility.'' Asked what kind of relief the government seeks in such cases, Ms. <PERSON> Burstion-Wade </PERSON> replied: `` The relief would be to protect minorities from disenfranchisement.'' <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunez </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicano </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said he understood the federal complaint against the county would involve alleged discrimination against Hispanics. `` We have always felt that the Latino community has been without power in that they have been fragmented, and they have not been able to exercise their voting ability,'' <PERSON> Nunez </PERSON> said. `` We are aware that county counsel has received a letter from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Deane </PERSON> <PERSON> Dana </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervisors </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement. `` He is reviewing it and will be advising the board. Until that process is complete, we will not have any comment beyond that.'' <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON>'s letter first was revealed publicly in Thursday editions of the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, which cited anonymous sources. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> filed a similar lawsuit in 1985 that forced the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to shift a district from the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fernando </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> to the city's largely Hispanic east side. The suit led to the election to the City Council of former Assemblywoman <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Molina </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> based its 1985 complaint on the 1965 Voting Rights Act, which prohibits redistricting that causes minority residents to have `` less opportunity than other members -LRB- of the community -RRB- to participate in the political process and to elect representatives of their choice.'' The lawsuit claimed that the city's 1982 plan splintered the political influence of Hispanics by spreading them thinly over many districts.
