<DATELINE>PORTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet experts accused the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of undermining progress on a global chemical weapons ban, but still expressed optimism that 20 years of talks would soon culminate in an agreement. Leaders of the 13-member Soviet delegation told a news conference that the talks sorely need a political initiative from <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and British leaders. However, just days before <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> get together in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for their fourth summit, the Soviet chemical weapons experts took a tough line against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> resumption of chemical weapons production. `` Such steps undoubtedly run counter to the aims of a chemical warfare convention,'' said <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazarkin </PERSON>, chief Soviet negotiator at the 40-nation <ORGANIZATION> Geneva </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on Disarmament, where the chemical weapons ban talks have been taking place. The news conference Thursday ended the Soviets' three-day visit here, the first time they have been at a chemical warfare facility in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuntsevich </PERSON>, deputy commander of the Soviets' chemical troops, said current <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production of binary weapons _ in which elements that are harmless on their own become lethal when combined _ is dangerous, `` uncontrollable and unverifiable. He said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision to end an 18-year moratorium on chemical weapons production last December raised Soviet suspicions that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> plans to supply binary weapons to its <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies. Still, <PERSON> Nazarkin </PERSON> appeared more optimistic than his British counterpart at the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> talks, Ambassador <PERSON> Tessa </PERSON> <PERSON> Solesby </PERSON>, that a verifiable agreement on the development, production and stockpiling of chemical weapons can be reached soon. `` The international negotiations in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> have actually entered the decisive stage of development ... We firmly believe that this convention will be achievable soon,'' <PERSON> Nazarkin </PERSON> said. `` In order to overcome the differences that still remain,'' he said, `` what we need is impetuses to solve the problems at a political level, not a technical level.'' But <PERSON> Solesby </PERSON> said getting <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> to give the negotiations a political push will not solve the main problem of verification. `` It is not a matter of lack of political will. ... It's the technical difficulties that remain,'' she said. The Soviets and their British hosts stressed the historic significance of the three-day visit to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Porton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Down </LOCATION> in southwest <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. But they disagreed on the size of the Soviet stockpile and the wisdom of setting a timetable for reaching a final agreement. <PERSON> Nazarkin </PERSON> said `` the successful outcome of negotiations depends on a time limit to settle and tackle all the unresolved problems.'' <PERSON> Solesby </PERSON> said: `` We do not feel artificial time limits are helpful.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said last year that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has a 50,000-ton stockpile. Western estimates have put it at 300,000 tons. <PERSON> Nazarkin </PERSON> insisted the Soviets had not lied about the size of their stockpile and said inspectors may see it as soon as an agreement is signed. He accused the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of inflating their estimates to justify the start of binary weapons production. He said the Soviet stockpile was now at parity with the American stockpile, which he also estimated at 50,000 tons. But <PERSON> Nazarkin </PERSON> expressed concern that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> binary weapons production could change the balance. The Americans have not disclosed the size of their stockpile but Western estimates put it at 30,000 tons. <PERSON> Solesby </PERSON> said <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> started producing binary weapons to counter Soviet production and replace its own aging stockpiles. During their visit to the 7,000-acre Porton Down facility, the Soviets held wide-ranging talks with British experts and watched <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> soldiers respond to a simulated enemy nerve gas attack. In July, a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> delegation will visit the chemical warfare facility at <LOCATION> Shikhany </LOCATION> in eastern <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>. Last October, specialists from the <ORGANIZATION> Geneva </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> visited <LOCATION> Shikhany </LOCATION>, where they were shown chemical weapons which seemed to date from the 1950s. The following month, Soviet inspectors visited a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> chemical weapons disposal plant at <LOCATION> Toole </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, where they were shown techniques for destroying old gas munitions.
