<HEAD>`The Greatest Show On Earth' Heads For Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For the first time in its uniquely American history, <ORGANIZATION> Ringling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Barnum </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> <PERSON> Circus </PERSON> is staging a colossal three-ring assault on the land of sushi and sumo wrestling. `` We are coming to entertain you!'' boomed <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Holst </PERSON>, the show's associate producer and former ringmaster, at a <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> news conference Thursday Flanked by five clowns, two jungling acrobats and a hula-hoop artist, he smiled and intoned, `` It is our hope and our interest that you will smile and laugh, and hide your eyes in fear.'' For 15 weeks starting in July, Japanese kids of all ages will be dazzled by daring trapeze acts, animal tamers, 25 clowns, 16 elephants, 14 lions, and assorted camels, llamas, dogs and chimpanzees under a big top. Coordinating trans-Pacific transportation for beasts, about 300 humans and 100 tractor-trailer loads of lighting and sound equipment and supplies in the circus' first overseas trip are enough to astound. <PERSON> Holst </PERSON> estimates Ringling Bros. spent at least $ 10 million for the production. The big top goes up this summer in <LOCATION> Sapporo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION>. Organizers hope to attract as many as 1.2 million Japanese and already are planning a 25-week run in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> next year. `` We are not interested in the short-term profit,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gold </PERSON>, Ringling marketing supervisor. `` We want to build a tradition. The Japanese public may have seen a circus before, but they've never the ` Greatest Show on Earth.''' Japanese got a sneak preview this week when <PERSON> Ringling </PERSON>'s promotional team unleased the clowns, jugglers, and hula-hoopist in full costume on the streets and television airwaves of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> `` Humor is universal,'' said blue-haired <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudert </PERSON>, whose nose was painted red. `` At first people are kind of surprised. But they really like slapstick.'' The ringmaster will continue to herald the acts in English, hoping Japanese audiences will pay close attention to his arm as he points to the various rings. Acts among the 130-member troop will include the Human Cannonball and the Globe of Death, in which two men on motorcycles race simultaneously inside a large chain-link ball, sometimes with their wives standing in the middle. `` We do n't know if what we're bringing will offend people,'' Gold acknowledged. `` Like today, -LRB- the Japanese sponsor -RRB- wanted to take the clowns around to some newspapers. I said, why do n't you take four, and I'll take one with me. `` He said no _ in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, four is an unlucky number. It means death,'' <PERSON> Gold </PERSON> said. He shrugged and raised his eyebrows. `` I did n't know that. Ticket prices will run $ 40 a head _ about the cost of a ticket to a rock concert here _ compared with a maximum of $ 12 in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` We cost maybe twice the price of a movie,'' Gold said. `` But where else can you see 250 people and animals risking their lives?''
