<SECOND>PM-Crash-SEC, Bjt,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Seeks Jurisdiction Over Chicago Futures Markets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is declaring its independence from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration by pushing its own proposals in the regulatory turf war that has followed the October stock market crash. A sharply divided commission voted 3-2 to ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for jurisdiction over the stock index futures markets in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, an area now regulated by a sister agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Members voting for the proposal noted that the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> already regulates the trading of stocks and stock options and said that it was only logical that the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> also oversee trading of futures contracts based on stocks. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> has already lost on the issue in an interagency working group formed to develop administration policy on market reform. The panel, whose members represented the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>, issued a report last week calling for no major legislative initiatives. Democrats in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> reacted with dismay to the working group's recommendations, which all but preclude the chances of a market bill this year Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, D-Wis., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, called them `` pitiful. However, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s move to stake out an independent position pleased Democrats looking for a means to rekindle sentiment for change. `` The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> today distinguished itself from the do-nothing strategists of the rest of this administration,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee with jurisdiction over the stock markets `` The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> has demonstrated intelligence, courage and common sense,'' he said in a statement. Aides to <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> are drafting a bill that would transfer jurisdiction of equity-related futures from the commodity commission to the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>. However, two members of the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> do not want that authority. Commission member <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischman </PERSON> argued that each commission was best qualified to oversee the separate markets. `` We come from different backgrounds. ... We wear different spectacles,'' he said. Commission member <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grundfest </PERSON> said he agreed with the goal of more consistent regulation, but said that seeking to take over part of the commodity commission's jurisdiction would only cause rancor and provoke a `` firestorm'' in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, where separate committees oversee the two agencies. `` I think we could have and should have proceeded on the path of cooperation. That could have gotten us a lot of what we wanted to achieve. ... We have instead embarked on a path I would describe as regulatory imperialism,'' he said. However, commission Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> said that <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> control of stock and stock futures regulation flows logically from the recommendations of an earlier presidential task force, composed of members of the financial community. The so-called <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> task force, headed by investment banker <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, said the futures and stock markets are economically one. `` I think it's time we move to what I think is a rational way of regulating that interlinked market,'' <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> said. He was supported by Commissioners <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> and <PERSON> Aulana </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> voted unanimously to offer four other recommendations to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and decided to withhold one for futher discussion. In one, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> said it should have emergency power to call trading halts, delay the opening of markets or close them early. The commission would have to seek permission from the president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to continue a trading halt beyond 24 hours, and the president would have the power to overturn any emergency action by the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>. If enacted, the emergency authority would reverse the current arrangement, which requires the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> to seek presidential permission before calling a trading halt. The commission also asked for authority to require the reporting of securities trades of larger than $ 5 million. That is intended to make it easier for the agency to track index arbitrage, a form of computer trading involving the simultaneous sale of large groups of stocks and futures contracts.
