<SECOND>PM-Holiday Trafffic,0132</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Safety Council Projects Memorial Day Traffic-Accident
Toll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The long Memorial Day weekend that begins today may claim the lives of 380 to 480 people in traffic accidents, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> has estimated. The three-day holiday period begins at 6 p.m. today, local time, and ends at midnight Monday for counting purposes. During last year's Memorial Day weekend, 416 people died in traffic accidents, the Chicago-based council said Thursday. The worst Memorial Day traffic toll in the last quarter century was recorded in 1968, when 629 people died. The lowest recorded toll, in 1982, was 341. About 390 traffic deaths on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> roadways would be projected for a non-holiday, three-day weekend this time of year, statistics clerk <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> said Thursday.
</TEXT>
