<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A decision by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to loosen up acreage controls on 1989 wheat production `` indicates the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> intends to be a grain seller, not a grain storer,'' says the president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wheat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Johannsen </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Bayard </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, wheat farmer, referred in a statement released Thursday to an earlier <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> announcement that producers would be required to idle no more than 10 percent of their wheat base acreage to qualify for 1989 program benefits. The acreage set-aside was 27.5 percent for 1988. But <PERSON> Johannsen </PERSON> said the smaller land-idling requirement `` requires a continuing federal commitment'' to operate the Export Enchancement Program, or <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION>, which has helped reduce surplus <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat stockpiles. Under <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION>, selected foreign countries _ including the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> _ have been able to buy huge quantities of wheat at subsidized prices. `` We intend to work closely with <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to see that existing export assistance programs are used effectively and that the past oversupply of wheat not be allowed to reoccur,'' he said. `` For 50 years _ and often to its detriment _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has held virtually all the world's surplus grain,'' <PERSON> Johannsen </PERSON> added. `` With the 1989 wheat program, we shift that burden to our competitors.''
