<HEAD>Government Scientists Plan Acid Rain Study in Illinois</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government scientists are planning to spend a month studying the skies over <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> to learn how much effect summer storms have on acid rain. The project, which will start on June 1 and continue for four weeks, will use both radar and airborne measurements to see how long and how far storms carry pollutants, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` If you're going to get a handle on pollutants that are put into the atmosphere and what their impact will be downwind, you have to know what happens to them aloft,'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said Thursday. `` How much of the pollutants fall out within a 10 - or 20 - or 50-mile range of the source he asked. `` How much of it gets carried aloft and moved further along? What are the conditions that cause it to either fall out early on or get carried along for some distance? A scientist always has to know why.'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said that the study being undertaken by his agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>, federal research laboratories, several universities and the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survey </ORGANIZATION> will provide `` a body of knowledge from which the policymakers can reach decisions on acid rain.'' During the four-week study based at <LOCATION> Willard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Champaign </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, one team of scientists will use flying laboratories to see how storms redistribute pollutants, while another team will use a new radar technique to observe the movement of pollution in the troposphere, seven to 10 miles above the ground, <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said. He said a team from the oceanic and atmospheric administration's <ORGANIZATION> Aeronomy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, will be conducting a related study to test two kinds of Doppler radars, one for monitoring upper-level winds and the other for winds near the surface At the same time, the Illinois Water Survey will use its rainfall-collection network to determine how much pollution is contained in rainfall from local storms.
