<HEAD>Rent Voucher Program to Be Extended to Rural Families</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some rural families will soon be able to take advantage of a federal program that is helping 110,000 urban residents pay their rent, sometimes with cash left over for the renter. Housing and Urban Development Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> announced Thursday that <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s housing voucher program was being extended into 50 public housing districts in 13 states. Initially, the program will aid only 2,178 rural families, but officials say they hope it can be expanded to other housing districts and states. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> has asked for funding to issue an additional 100,000 vouchers in fiscal 1989. The largest numbers of rural vouchers will be available in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s announcement <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoenberger </PERSON>, deputy federal housing commissioner, said areas in those states and in nine others were chosen because they had public housing authorities that appear most ready to set up the rural programs in cooperation with the <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The voucher program, which began as an experimental alternative to public housing in 1984, became permanent under a law signed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> earlier this year. Qualified low-income families may be given housing vouchers worth the difference between 30 percent of their family income and the local `` payment standard'' for adequate housing in the area where they live. Officials said that <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> expects to be funding more single-family dwellings in rural communities than it does in cities, where most recipients live in apartments. The program contains what <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials call a `` shopping incentive,'' allowing renters to rent whatever kind of housing they want, rather than limiting them to public housing projects. `` We think it's a program with a great amount of sensitivity to it,'' <PERSON> Schoenberger </PERSON> said. He said that the vouchers allow people to receive aid without subjecting themselves to the social problems that often plague public housing projects. In a typical situation under either the rural or urban programs: A family might be earning $ 10,000 a year, meaning that it would be expected to pay 30 percent of its income or $ 3,000 in rent. If <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> determines the `` payment standard'' for an adequate unit for the family to be $ 5,000, the family would receive vouchers worth $ 2,000 a year. Recipients then can decide whether they want to pay $ 5,000 and use all of the voucher, stay in a $ 3,000 unit and use the additional funds for other needs, or pay more than $ 5,000 to further improve their lifestyle. In public housing, renters do n't see any of the assistance given by the government. Under the voucher program, an arrangement can be made to return money to the renters if they can find a unit that rents for less than the subsidy. <PERSON> Schoenberger </PERSON> said that there already may be a line of applicants for the rural vouchers in some housing authorites, but in others, there could be an `` opportunity to pretty much walk into the door and take advantage of it.'' Under the program, select <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> housing authorities will assist 441 famlies; <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, 422 families; <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, 380; <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, 225; and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, 130. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> will each be allowed 100 vouchers, while <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> will each serve 50 rural families, and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> will help 30.
