<TEXT>
 Democrats pushing for expanded AIDS testing and counseling say they had to drop a bitterly contested provision protecting AIDS victims from discrimination to get their bill moving. The bill, which provides $ 400 million next year and each of the following two years for AIDS testing, won voice vote approval on Thursday from the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> health subcommittee. The measure now goes to the full <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> for a vote, probably early next month. A similar bill is pending in a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee. The bill was welcomed by some in the gay community, even without the ban on discrimination, because of its provisions for counseling and confidentiality of test results. `` Even without the non-discrimination provision, it's worth having,'' said <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Levi </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gay </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lesbian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. Subcommittee chairman <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, D-Calif., said that the anti-discrimination provision was dropped because `` unfortunately, that policy is caught up in such controversy that we will not be able to pursue it at this time,'' Asked what went into the decision to drop it, an aide replied, `` Counting votes. <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>, D-Ore., said that they hoped they could eventually win a ban on discrimination against AIDS victims and carriers The discrimination ban not only would protect AIDS victims, but also encourage voluntary testing, <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> said, because `` many Americans will be reluctant to come forward for voluntary testing if they are then open to blatant discrimination on the basis of the results.'' `` We've got to keep pushing. That's the one key missing part,'' he added. <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> and <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> said that federal laws and policies clearly state that discrimination by the federal government and its contractors is not allowed. But `` there are some real questions about the private sector,'' <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> said. The bill authorizes new and expanded testing programs run by states, localities and private groups. Testing would have to be voluntary and accompanied by counseling. Anonymous testing and use of pseudonyms would be permitted to the extent possible under state laws. Under the measure, health professionals or others who violated confidentiality standards outlined in the bill, intentionally or negligently, could be fined up to $ 10,000 for each offense. On its third and final day of deliberations Thursday, the subcommittee agreed to an amendment saying that money in the bill can not be used for counseling `` that promotes or encourages, directly, homosexual or unsafe heterosexual activity or intravenous substance abuse.'' The amendment also says that counselors must supply `` the most current scientific knowledge available ... provided that any informational materials used are not obscene.'' The amendment arose after conservatives in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> complained that the Gay Men's Health Crisis in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, which receives federal money, produced an educational comic book and videotape that explicitly depicted homosexual acts. The panel also approved amendments requiring testing of people convicted of intravenous drug use, prostitution or a crime related to sexual assault, and making it a crime for a person to contribute to a blood bank or have sexual relations if he knows he has AIDS or carries the AIDS virus. Amendments requiring testing of marriage license applicants and hospital patients were rejected. The subcommittee also refused to require that public health authorities be given the names, addresses and phone numbers of people who do n't have AIDS but test positive for the virus that causes it. AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is transmitted through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring. There is no known cure for the disease, which damages the body's immune system.
</TEXT>
