<HEAD>House Members Lash Out at `Zero Tolerance' Drug Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> blames the public outcry over the new federal `` zero tolerance'' anti-drug policy on wealthy Americans whose boats are being seized by the government. Customs Commissioner <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON>, in his first appearance before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> since the policy began, said Thursday that seizures of vessels at sea after discoveries of miniscule amounts of illegal drugs were affecting `` arrogant stock brokers and smooth lawyers who think they're above the law.'' <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> told members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and navigation subcommittee that complaints were coming from `` rich people who have a lot of pull with the media, who have a lot of pull with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.'' The policy, he said, `` is supported by the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people.'' Joining <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> was Admiral <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, commandant of the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, who disputed lawmakers' complaints that his service was squandering money from its already tight budget. <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> told the legislators that the arrests and seizures were occurring only during routine patrols and inspections, saying, `` I am not wasting resources in this policy.'' Most members of the subcommittee, however, rejected the officials' claims and insisted that zero tolerance was a case of an overzealous government going too far. `` In the minds of the public, this is a government policy gone awry,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, the panel's ranking Republican. `` It symbolizes unfairness.'' The subcommittee's chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutto </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., was one of several lawmakers who complained that the seizure of fishing boats after crewmen were found to have tiny amounts of drugs was depriving innocent owners of a means to earn a living `` Innocent persons are being hurt more than users,'' he said. Some members of the panel engaged <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> in heated exchanges. Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>, complained to the Customs official about a small boat seized in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> after paraphernalia such as rolling paper and rolling machines were discovered. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said that such implements could be perfectly innocent and told <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON>, `` You're not helping the cause here at all. In fact, you're hurting it.'' Under the policy, Customs and <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officers finding small amounts of illegal drugs during searches conducted at sea have begun arresting people and seizing boats. The new procedures have resulted in the temporary seizure of such boats as the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> II </ORGANIZATION>, owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Woods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, after a crewman was found to have a tiny amount of marijuana. In addition, the $ 2.5 million yacht <ORGANIZATION> Ark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> and the Monkey Business _ the pleasure boat that former presidential candidate <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> sailed on with model <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> _ were seized after small quantities of drugs were discovered. Under new guidelines issued late last week, authorities finding small amounts of drugs on board vessels beyond the 12-mile limit now are seizing boats only if they appear to be involved in transporting drugs into the country. Some lawmakers defended the policy. Rep. <PERSON> Wally </PERSON> <PERSON> Herger </PERSON>, R-Calif., conceded that zero tolerance needs adjustments but said he believed the policy is sound Rep. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Clement </PERSON>, D-Tenn., said, `` My constituents want a tough policy, and that policy is that no amount of drugs is OK.'' <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said that the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has made 1,500 seizures _ mostly of automobiles crossing into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ since zero tolerance took <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> said 44 boats have so far been seized, 13 of which have already been released. The Customs Service implemented the policy on March 21, and the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> followed suit on April 11.
