<HEAD>House GOP Rebuffed in Effort to Renew Military Aid to Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House Republicans staged a legislative ambush in an attempt to renew military aid to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Contra rebels, but were rebuffed amid fears that such a move would upset delicate negotiations in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. In a surprise move, Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., sought Thursday to amend an intelligence bill to permit President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to dip into the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>'s contingency fund to finance future covert military aid to the rebels The measure was defeated, 214-190. Since 1983, the law authorizing intelligence operations has contained a prohibition on use of the spy agency's contingency fund to buy weapons and other supplies for the Contras. The ban was imposed after lawmakers became angered at the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>'s role in aiding the Nicaraguan war. <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON>'s amendment would have dropped the prohibition from the law. At present, the rebels can receive only humanitarian aid _ food, clothing and medicine _ from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> under a $ 17.7 million program approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year. Proponents of the move argued that things have gone badly for the rebels since <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> voted earlier this year to end military aid. The two sides are nearing the end of a two-month truce agreed to during talks at <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The Contra supporters said that the Nicaraguan government has taken advantage of the cease-fire to weaken the rebels and has failed to live up to promises made in a regional peace accord reached last year. Instead, they argued, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> have harassed peaceful anti-government demonstrators, arrested labor leaders and denied press freedom. Giving <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> the power to resume covert military aid any time after Oct. 1 would add pressure for the <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> regime to release political prisoners, restore civil liberties and hold free elections, supporters of the amendment argued. Opponents of the move noted that a new round of negotiations between the two warring sides was taking place in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> and said that there was still hope that a lasting peace could be achieved. `` I can not think of a more pernicious, ill-timed amendment,'' said Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonior </PERSON>, D-Mich. `` At the very minute that the Contras, who have struggled for three weeks to put their own act together, ... meet with the government of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, an amendment is offered to put the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> back into this war. In another attempt to pressure the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>, a group of conservative lawmakers announced plans to seek new military aid for the rebels if the <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> government fails to meet its obligations under the peace accord by the time the formal truce ends on May 31. Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, while declining to give precise figures, said the package would include substantial military and humanitarian aid, sufficient to last the Contras a year to 18 months.
