<HEAD>Gore Would Bring Southern Strength To Democratic Ticket</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One in a series of occasional profiles of vice presidential
prospects.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> remains on the list of possible <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidates for the vice presidency despite calling the job a `` political dead end'' when he was seeking the No. 1 spot on the ticket. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s prospects of joining the ticket declined in the estimation of some Democrats as a result of his attacks on both <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in the final weeks of his presidential campaign. He would bring to the ticket, however, credentials as a Southerner with proven popularity in the region. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> ended his 1988 presidential hopes after the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> primary in April, his campaign a failure outside of the region-wide victories in the Super Tuesday primaries. At 40 the youngest of the potential vice presidential nominees, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> remains in the speculation in part because of those Southern successes. Some observers contend that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the likely Democratic presidential nominee, needs a Southerner on the ticket if he is to carry any states in the region that is often crucial to Democratic electoral strategy. Other Southerners getting frequent mention are Sens. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> insisted throughout his campaign that he had no interest in the No. 2 job. He did not flatly rule it out, however. `` I have no interest in it _ might very well turn it down, indeed, and probably would,'' he said once. `` I think Vice President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will demonstrate again this year that it is a politi