TION> prep school and then <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>. His wife, <PERSON> Tipper </PERSON>, was a high school sweetheart, and she has become well-known in her own right for leading public crusades against violent and sexually explicit lyrics in music aimed at young people. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> worked as a newspaper reporter in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, and entered both divinity school and law school, not completing either. He quit law school after two years when the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> seat his father once held came open, and won election in 1976. He won election to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1984, when Republican <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> declined to run again. Although he has a congressional voting record decidedly more liberal than some of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>'s other members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> positioned himself in the presidential race to the right of most other Democratic contenders.
