<HEAD>Latest ABC-Post Poll Gives Dukakis 13-Point Lead Over Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic presidential front-runner, holds a 13-point lead over <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> nominee-to-be <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, according to a poll published today. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> leads <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> 53 percent to 40 percent, the survey by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> indicates. The poll also found that the vice president's unfavorability rating is nearly four times as great as that of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is viewed unfavorably by 37 percent and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> by 10 percent, the newspaper said. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor is favorably rated by 67 percent of those surveyed, to 50 percent for the vice president. The survey also indicated that the `` gender gap'' plays a part in <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' lead at this stage. Among women voters, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> holds a 2-1 lead, 61 percent to 33 percent. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has the advantage among male voters, but only of 4 percentage points, the newspaper said. The survey of 1,172 randomly selected registered voters nationwide also suggested, however, that the support of both candidates is `` soft'' and could easily shift between now and the November election. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' edge over <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> widened when compared to a similar Post-ABC poll conducted in March. In that survey, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had a 5-point lead. Several other polls conducted in recent weeks have given <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> a double-digit lead. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, 57 percent of the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> supporters said they backed the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor largely because they do n't want 