Extremists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Indian laborers died today of injuries suffered when a bomb went off in a crowded market in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, a northern Indian state racked by Sikh separatist violence. In another development, the federal government issued an ordinance banning the use of temples and shrines for political activity or the harboring of wanted criminals. President <PERSON> Ramaswami </PERSON> <PERSON> Venkataraman </PERSON> issued the ordinance on Thursday, aimed at ending Sikh extremists' use of the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> as a base for their separatist activities. The bomb, apparently hidden in a rickshaw, went off Thursday night in the town of <LOCATION> Phagwara </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Karpurthala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>, east of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. The Press Trust of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> news agency said 30 people were injured, most of them laborers from nearby work camps. The news agency said three of the victims were in serious condition at local hospitals. It quoted police as saying the bombing was the work of the <PERSON> Barbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalsa </PERSON> gang, one of a dozen Sikh extremist groups operating in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state. The news agency quoted <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Swaran </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> as saying police raided a number of the radicals' hideouts in a search for the bombers Sikh radicals, who have been waging a guerrilla war for an independent homeland in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> since 1982, recently stepped up attacks on Hindu migrant workers in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Government officials say that one-third of the estimated 700,000 Hindu migrants have fled to their homes in eastern <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, threatening to undermine <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>'s agricultural economy. The new