<FIRST>r i PM-Laos-Bombs     05-27 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Laos-Bombs,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>After 15 Years Of War, U.S. Bombs Still Deadly, Aid Workers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENTIANE, Laos (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mother of 10 tending her garden, two workers digging a canal and several children are among the most recent victims of American cluster bombs dropped on <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> during the Vietnam War. It's been 15 years since the last American sorties were flown over this Southeast Asian nation, but the death toll continues to mount, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> relief workers say. Buried in the jungle of this land-locked nation, the fruit-shaped bombs, each about the size of a tennis ball, still maim and kill. Although total casualty figures have not been compiled, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Friends </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Mennonite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> say hundreds have lost their lives or limbs to the devices since the end of the war. Since January, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> aid workers say, the bombs have killed 10 people and injured 12 others on <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>' Plain of Jars. In May, five bombs were found by a joint U.S.-Laotian team searching for the remains of Americans missing in action at a crash site in <LOCATION> Savannakhet </LOCATION> province. Nicknamed `` guavas'' or `` oranges'' by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops or `` bombies'' by the Laotians, the anti-personnel devices were dropped during the 1964-73 air war over <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Rumpf </PERSON> of American Friends says the Laotian government has not worked to clear the bombs. <PERSON> Rumpf </PERSON> said the once strategic Plain of Jars remains perhaps the most dangerous zone and large tracts of land can be farmed only at great risk. During the war, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> dropped thousands of bombs on the area, turning it into a moonscape. Laotians say two tons of bombs fell for every human being on the plain. The area was a key communications and transport route between <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and was used by Communist forces as a supply route. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Friends </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Mennonite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> _ the only <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> aid organizations allowed into communist <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> to date _ operate here on a small scale. Local officials reportedly are eager for outside help, but the central Laotian government has rejected tentative offers for official <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> assistance. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for its part has given the cold shoulder to such proposals for aid. <PERSON> Rumpf </PERSON> has spent five years in <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> since the 1975 communist victory over the U.S.-backed <LOCATION> Vientiane </LOCATION> government. His group has provided farmers with 20,000 shovels, said to be far safer than hoes, which tend to set off the bombs on impact. The Mennonites have offered to supply Laotians with a custom-built tractor with a special detonator for bomb-littered fields but volunteers to drive the machine have been lacking. Now, the Mennonites are awaiting word from <LOCATION> Vientiane </LOCATION> authorities on a program to set up bomb-clearing teams in each district of <LOCATION> Xiengkhouang </LOCATION> province, where the Plain of Jars is located. The proposal was submitted a year ago. <PERSON> Rumpf </PERSON> said that with the passing of time the small bombs have become especially dangerous. Monsoon rains and erosion have driven some beneath the surface of fields while others `` float'' back up to the topsoil. Villagers find the weapons a good source of income. The innards of the bombs are sold to the Vietnamese as ball bearings for bicyles, and casings are turned into wick lamps. The metal from larger bombs is fashioned into household utensils. Statistics vary, but standard histories say more bomb tonnage was dropped on <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> than on any country in history. Sometimes cited is the figure 2 million tons _ more than the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unleashed in all of World War II. The Plain of Jars was ravaged, as were areas along the vital communist supply route, the Ho Chi Minh trail, in southern <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>. Few buildings were left standing, farm animals were killed by the thousands and refugees swarmed from these regions.
</TEXT>
