<FIRST>r a PM-Exercise-Fetuses     05-27 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exercise-Fetuses,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fetal Heart Rates Slow After Very Vigorous Maternal Exercise,
Study Finds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Exercise is good for pregnant women, but one-third of the 45 expectant mothers who pushed themselves to the limit in brief workouts slowed the heart rates of their unborn babies, researchers say. Whether diminished heart rates hurt fetuses is unclear, but it could deprive them of needed oxygen, researchers said in a study in today's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Milder exercise does n't have the same effect, and the findings suggest that higher exercise levels than currently recommended are safe for pregnant women, said lead researcher Dr. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON>. `` The study is encouraging that women can continue exercising during pregnancy at levels reminiscent of that before pregnancy,'' he said in a telephone interview Thursday. `` On the other hand, I would caution women against exceeding 145 to 150 heartbeats a minute -LRB- for their own heart rate -RRB- because we do n't know what effect it has on the fetus.'' The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Obstetricians </ORGANIZATION> and Gynecologists recommends that an expectant mother not exercise beyond a level that raises her heart rate to 140 beats per minute, <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> said. But that recommendation was largely precautionary, and `` we can give women a little more latitude than before,'' he said. The 45 women in the study were 4 -LCB- months to 7 -LCB- months pregnant, and had an average age of 29. Fetal heart rates were measured at moderate and maximum exercise levels by <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON>, physiologist <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sady </PERSON>, and other researchers at <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. They found that maximum exercise _ when women peddled stationary bicycles against increasing resistance until they were unwilling or unable to continue _ produced brief episodes of slowed heart rates in 15 fetuses. Two other fetuses experienced slowed heart rates linked to moderate exercise, they said. The researchers believe any oxygen shortage was mild because tests given the unborn babies 30 minutes after the initial measurements were normal. The slowed heart rates did not appear to give rise to later problems, the researchers said. Three of the 45 infants studied as fetuses died within five weeks of birth, but of apparently unrelated causes. Some of the study's subjects had exercised vigorously on a regular basis before becoming pregnant and some had not, but that did not appear to affect fetal heartbeats, the researchers said. Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, a researcher at <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hershey </LOCATION>, said in a telephone interview that the most important consideration is tailoring the level of exercise to the individual.
