<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's plans for random drug testing of all federal prison employees have been put on hold for three weeks more by a judge. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Weigel </PERSON> on Thursday extended the restraining order to June 16. The order had been sought in a lawsuit by the American Federation of Government Employees, the country's largest federal workers union. The testing was to have started last Monday. <PERSON> Weigel </PERSON> issued a temporary restraining order May 20, saying constitutional problems were raised by testing law-abiding employees not suspected of wrongdoing. The delay has triggered a hiring freeze by the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prisons </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lepley </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lepley </PERSON>, noting that the agency has tested job applicants since 1984, asked <PERSON> Weigel </PERSON> to exempt applicants from his order. The judge did not make an immediate decision. The program stems from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s 1986 order that federal employees in sensitive jobs receive drug testing. The prisons agency was one of the first agencies scheduled to begin testing and the first to order random tests for all employees on the theory that all hold sensitive jobs. The union, which claims 9,400 prison employees among its 750,000 members, contends in its suit that testing without suspicion of drug use by an individual violates constitional standards for unreasonable search. The suit also claims violations of federal laws forbidding discrimination against the handicapped and requiring that employee discipline be related to job performance. Union attorney <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said Thursday that the government's safety justifications were a smokescreen `` This program was not designed for safety,'' <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said. `` Testing was developed as a political reaction'' to administration frustration at its inability to curb drug importation, he said. `` Federal employees were an available scapegoat.'' <PERSON> Lepley </PERSON> acknowledged that testing does not directly measure inability to do a job, but said it could reveal the potential for abusing drugs, would discourage employees from using them and would help keep drugs out of prisons. Prison employees have a reduced expectation of privacy, he said. In a separate suit, the union has challenged the entire drug testing program, which would cover 345,000 employees in 40 agencies. Another suit was filed in the same court Thursday by an employee group, the <ORGANIZATION> Overseas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, challenging plans for random drug testing of more than 9,600 teachers in schools run by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military dependents in 20 countries.
