<HEAD>Government To Renovate Ancient Tibetan Palace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government plans to renovate the ancient palace of the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> that overlooks the Tibetan capital of <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> _ at an estimated cost of $ 8 million, an official newspaper reported today. The <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said portions of the <LOCATION> Potala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palace </LOCATION> have been cracked or damaged by worms over the centuries. It said more than $ 1 million was spent on repairs in 1981, but that this was `` far from enough.'' The planned renovation will include repairs to 720 square feet of frescoes, the report said. The vast Potala Palace, which now includes hundreds of rooms stacked 13 stories high, was begun in the 7th century as a pavilion. It was greatly enlarged in the 17th century. It includes living quarters for the Dalai Lama, <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>'s traditional god-king, mausoleums of seven previous Dalai Lamas, ceremonial halls, treasure store rooms, government offices, a prison and a monastery Since 1959, however, when the current <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> fled to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, only a few monks have been allowed to remain in the <LOCATION> Potala </LOCATION>, and it serves mainly as a museum for tourists. The <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> fled <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> during a failed uprising by thousands of Tibetans against communist Chinese rule, imposed nine years earlier. Most of the temples and religious sites in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> were destroyed or badly damaged by radical bands of Red Guards during <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s Cultural Revolution from 1966-76 <LOCATION> Tibetan </LOCATION> activists claim <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> is renovating the temples now to lure more foreigners to <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> and profit from their tourist dollars. The activists have staged two large demonstrations over the past year in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> calling for an independent <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>. Both were crushed by Chinese authorities.
