<FIRST>r a PM-AZTStudy     05-27 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AZT Study,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>AZT Might Reduce Spread Of AIDS To Sexual Partners, Study Finds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 AZT could make AIDS patients less infectious to their sexual partners, according to researchers who found high levels of the virus-fighting drug in the semen of patients treated with it. However, the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> researchers caution in today's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> that larger and more detailed studies are needed to determine if AZT can reduce the risk of spreading the virus. `` Our worst scenario is that some patients taking AZT will decide that they no longer need to follow existing -LRB- safer-sex -RRB- recommendations,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Balfour </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> virologist and a member of the research team. Researchers are trying to learn whether the drug even lowers the amount of AIDS virus in the semen, said study author Dr. <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, who is with the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. If so, said <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, it raises the possibility that AZT could lower the risk of virus transmission to sexual partners. Health experts strongly urge people who even suspect that they may have the AIDS virus to forgo sexual intercourse, or at least to use a condom to reduce the risk of the virus spreading. At best, AZT probably would reduce, rather than eliminate, the risk of the virus spreading, and no one yet knows by how much, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> explained. The abstinence-or-condom recommendations are expected to continue as the first line of defense regardless of what further studies find, he added. Semen has been the primary means by which the AIDS virus has been transmitted since the epidemic began in 1981. Infected blood is the other major transmission route. AZT is not a cure for AIDS, but it's the only drug so far that has shown a clear-cut ability to extend some AIDS patients' lives. It is being taken by at least 25,000 people who have the AIDS virus, <PERSON> Balfour </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> study found that the level of AZT in six patients was typically several times higher in their semen than in their blood. These AZT levels would be enough to keep the virus from multiplying in a test tube, but <PERSON> Balfour </PERSON> said the results might be different in the body. In addition, the drug is n't designed to get rid of all the virus, only to keep it from growing, he said. Three of the patients in the study have AIDS, and three others were ill with less severe symptoms called ARC, or AIDS-related complex. The study was the first major look at how AZT concentrates in body fluids other than blood, the researchers said.
