<HEAD>Iranians Fortify After Defeat, Bodies Scattered on Battlefield</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUT SWADI, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Iranian troops were busy building new fortifications east of this tiny frontier post after <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> drove them back into their own territory in a lightning attack east of the port city of <LOCATION> Basra </LOCATION>. Reporters on a government-organized tour of the war front Thursday saw the bodies of dozens of Iranian soldiers scattered on this dusty plain along with their light weapons, rocket-propelled grenade launchers and hand grenades. A field hospital built in a trench and well protected with concrete walls was abandoned. Its equipment was scattered on the floor along with more bodies of Iranian soldiers. Reporters were shown a small number of Iranian prisoners of war, some in their mid-teens, others in their 60s. <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> officers would not let reporters speak to them. From this border post 10 miles east of <LOCATION> Basra </LOCATION>, Iranian troops were visible in the distance, hastily building new fortifications. The Iraqi officers said their forces, led by elite Presidential Guards, routed the Iranians in a five-pronged offensive launched Wednesday morning that lasted 10 hours. A senior officer, speaking on condition his name and rank not be divulged, said <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> troops backed by tanks, artillery, jet fighters and helicopter gunships retook 50 square miles of <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> territory. The attack was spearheaded by tanks, part of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s heavily mechanized armed forces, and faced more lightly armed but sometimes fanatical Iranian Revolutionary Guards and volunteers. The officer said those Iranian troops that were n't killed or wounded `` fled to the other side of the border.'' This observation post is where the Iranians pushed their troops into <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in a January 1987 offensive that eventually petered out just six miles from <LOCATION> Basra </LOCATION>. The southern city, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s second largest, is also its only sea port. Iranian army jeeps, trucks and ammunition stocks, some in good shape, were abandoned by the Iranians along tracks they had built to approach their main defense points. Western military analysts estimated that between 35,000 and 40,000 Iraqi troops took part in this week's offensive, but reliable casualty estimates were not yet available. Reporters counted 400 Iranian prisoners of war being held here. The analysts say about 25,000 Iranians were believed killed in the 1987 offensive and perhaps 10,000 Iraqis. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has gone on the offensive recently after more than two years of defensive tactics in the war, which began in September 1980. On April 18, <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> forces retook the <LOCATION> Faw </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, which had been in Iranian hands since February 1986.
