<FIRST>r a PM-Bernardin-Euthanasia     05-27 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bernardin-Euthanasia,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cardinal Renews Opposition To Euthanasia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cardinal <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernardin </PERSON> urged Roman Catholics and non-Catholics to oppose efforts to legalize euthanasia, but said opponents must work for alternatives for the incurably ill such as hospices. `` As individuals and as a society, we have the positive obligation to protect life,'' <PERSON> Bernardin </PERSON> said in a speech Thursday to the Center for Clinical Medical Ethics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospitals </ORGANIZATION> and Clinics. `` We have the negative obligation not to destroy or injure human life directly, especially the life of the innocent and vulnerable.'' <PERSON> Bernardin </PERSON> suggested that funding for hospice programs in hospitals or patients' homes could come from insurance or public sources. `` In this way we can eliminate many of the legitimate concerns that may motivate people to consider euthanasia, which otherwise would be unacceptable to them and society,'' he said. The cardinal said his position against mercy killing does not include keeping alive by extraordinary medical procedures or machines `` those who should be allowed a natural death.'' He said he was `` convinced that we are not morally obliged to do everything that is technically possible'' to keep terminally ill patients alive. `` In other words, there are cases where we would not be obliged to provide nutrition and hydration. He said the challenge was to develop a public policy `` to protect against an attitude that could erode respect for the inviolable dignity of human life.'' But such a policy should not create categories or priorities of people `` whose lives no longer need be protected,'' he said. The cardinal said his remarks were prompted by the increased public discussion of euthanasia following advances in medical technology that can artificially prolong a patient's life. The issue has been widely debated since the Chicago-based Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> published a letter in January by an anonymous doctor describing the mercy killing of a terminally ill cancer patient. `` The fear, then, of the pain and discomfort of a life prolonged inappropriately has led to an erosion of the natural instinct to preserve one's life,'' the cardinal said. `` In certain critical decisions involving living and dying, many perceive that the focus of concern many no longer be the good of the patient'' but what will best protect the doctor and hospital from legal action, he said.
