<HEAD>Police Arrest Protesting Employees At Luxury Hotel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, `Police, who ...' to UPDATE with fines
paid and workers released; CORRECTS spelling of Carlton throughout;
SUBS 9th pvs, `Larry MacArtney ...' to CORRECT spelling to
Macartney and UPDATE with hotel seeking meeting with workers</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Baton-wielding riot police today arrested 245 black employees of a luxury hotel as they demonstrated against a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company that is canceling its contract to manage the hotel. The <ORGANIZATION> Westin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotels </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> had managed the <ORGANIZATION> Carlton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> for 15 years. It reportedly decided to pull out of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> because of pressure from the anti-apartheid movement. Hotel guests, including a contingent of travel agents from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, looked on in amazement as police ordered the chanting protesters to disperse, then moved in with batons to begin the arrests. Police, who have authority to declare virtually any outdoor gathering illegal, said 142 men and 103 women were arrested. The workers were released several hours later after the hotel management paid $ 50 fines for each worker. Payment of the fines acknowledges guilt for the gathering. During the first arrests, some protesters were beaten and flung into police vans. Other employees _ including cooks in chef's hats and a doorman in top hat and tails _ voluntarily moved toward the vehicles to be taken to police headquarters. <PERSON> Westin </PERSON> announced last month that it would withdraw on June 6 as manager of the Carlton. Workers carried signs accusing <PERSON> Westin </PERSON> of exploitation and told reporters that the firm should pay them severance bonuses as part of its disinvestment. The <PERSON> Carlton </PERSON>, one of the two luxury hotels in central <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, is owned by the property division of <ORGANIZATION> Anglo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s largest conglomerate. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Macartney </PERSON>, the hotel's marketing director, He said the workers' contracts were with the hotel owners, not with <PERSON> Westin </PERSON>, and were not affected by the disinvestment. He said the management wanted to meet with the workers to explain the situation and hear complaints. Before the confrontation with police, the protesters _ including maids, bellhops and waiters _ trotted around the block on which the <PERSON> Carlton </PERSON> and an adjoining high-rise office building stand. Inside the hotel, white employees served breakfast in the restaurant and made beds, while departing guests carried their own luggage. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
