<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sikh extremists killed nine people in the northern state of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> today. The government said it would cut a 100-yard buffer zone around the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> to keep militants out of <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine. On Thursday, President <PERSON> Ramaswami </PERSON> <PERSON> Venkataraman </PERSON> issued an ordinance making it illegal for temples and other religious sites to be used for political purposes. It also would make harboring a wanted criminal in a shrine punishable by imprisonment or a fine. Home Minister <PERSON> Buta </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, whose ministry is responsible for internal security, said today the government would clear houses and shops from around the Golden Temple complex in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. The actions were aimed at stemming the rising violence by <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> extremists, who have been waging a guerrilla war in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> since 1982 for more political autonomy or an independent homeland. The Sikhs, whose religion was formed about 500 years ago as an alternative to <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> and Islam, say they are discriminated against by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s majority Hindus. The latest killings raised to more than 1,180 the number of deaths blamed on <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> extremists in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> since the start of the year. In all of 1987, 1,030 people died. The decision to cut a corridor around the walled shrine follows a 10-day siege by police and paramilitary troops to drive Sikh radicals from the temple. The siege ended May 18 with the surrender of the last of 200 Sikh extremists and sympathizers from the complex. At least 46 people were killed in the confrontation, most of them militants. The police continue to keep a cordon around the shrine, but their security efforts are hampered because dozens of shops, houses and narrow alleys beside the complex provide cover for militants moving around in the area. <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chidambaram </PERSON>, <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s deputy, told the news conference that about 700 families and 300 shops would be displaced. He said the government would set up a resettlement program for those forced to move.
