<HEAD>World's Tallest Offshore Drilling Platform Heads For Gulf</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs with operation underway; PICKS UP 6th graf
pvs, `Shell has ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INGLESIDE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seven tugboats this morning began hauling a drilling platform to its home off the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> coast where, when erected, it will stand higher than the world's tallest building. `` It looks smaller and smaller the farther away it gets,'' <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON>, installation superintendent for the unwieldy engineering marvel, said as the launch got under way. `` My job's just beginning.'' The world's tallest offshore drilling platform, dubbed Bullwinkle, weighs 50,000 tons and is 1,365 feet long. After its two drilling rigs are installed in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, it will weigh 78,000 tons and stand 1,615 feet high _ 161 feet higher than the world's tallest building, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s Sears Tower. `` It is kind of a letdown when you finally see it go out,'' <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON>, project manager for <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Offshore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday while overseeing last-minute preparations. Sterling has been in charge of Bullwinkle during the three years it has taken to build the platform. Shell estimates the total cost of the Bullwinkle project at $ 500 million. Half of that is for building and installing the platform and preparing it for drilling, while the remainder will go toward development drilling, permanent production facilities and a pipeline to move the oil to shore, the company said. A steady stream of area residents stopped by the yard Thursday night to take a final look at the huge drilling jacket, which towers above the platform's 4 -LCB- - acre base and is visible several miles away in <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION> The jacket will hold the drilling rigs. `` I came out to see it one last time,'' said <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Waddle </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION>, as Bullwinkle loomed in front of him. Workers expect to take about three days to pull the structure about 380 miles to its destination, some 150 miles southwest of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Installation will be completed in about three months. Twenty-eight pilings for Bullwinkle will be driven 400 feet into the sea floor and secured with concrete. Bullwinkle is designed to withstand at least a 72-foot hurricane wave, with the ability to sway at least six feet without stress damage. <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> estimates that production will begin in the first quarter of 1989, and will peak at 50,000 barrels of oil a day in 1991 and 90 million cubic feet of natural gas a day in 1992. It has an estimated life span of 35 years, according to the company. The Bullwinkle project was conceived when oil fetched well above $ 20 a barrel, <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON> said. But, he added, `` even today at $ 15 it's an economic -LRB- profitable -RRB- venture.''
