der gap'' seemed to be far worse than that ever faced by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who also had more support among men than women voters. `` It's largely for institutional reasons. It's got more to do with party than it does with candidates. But it did close in 1984 as we got close to the election, although it never closed completely. There is an institutional and a party gender gap and we're going to make a very strong effort to close it,'' <PERSON> Teeter </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> staff chief <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> said that the vice president would focus on domestic affairs in sessions on Friday and Saturday and would meet with economic advisers next Tuesday and Wednesday to flesh out his fall campaign positions. <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was not overly concerned about recent polls that showed him falling behind <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` There are some advantages to being the underdog and fighting back,'' <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> said. Campaigning in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> on Thursday, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> focused on the war against drugs, calling for a requirement that government contracts be awarded only to companies that have `` drug free'' programs for their employes. Aides said that the proposal could involve some form of mandatory drug testing for all companies doing busines with the government, although details had not been worked out. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also called for an international drug `` strike force'' that would seek out and destroy drug crops wherever they were found. And he said he would put `` a single military figure'' in charge of coordinating <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> participation in such an effort. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said that the overall anti-drug effort in his administration would be headed by the vice president.
