<HEAD>UN Relief Coordinator Sees War Delaying Refugee Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official said Friday that continuing warfare in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> could delay the return of more than 5 million war refugees. Prince <PERSON> Sadruddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Aga </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>' relief coordinator for <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, said he could not predict how many of the refugees plan to return. Most are in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. `` It's common sense that people do not feel very encouraged to go home if they know there is still fighting,'' <PERSON> Sadruddin </PERSON> told reporters. But `` the one incentive which will encourage them to go home as quickly as possible is that they love their country and feel very homesick,'' he said. He said respecting last month's <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords, which call for the withdrawal of Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and the safe and voluntary return of refugees, was `` paramount'' for peace. Soviet troops entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in 1979 to help the Afghan government fight a civil war with anti-communist guerrillas, and they began pulling out of the country May 15. The guerrillas have said they will continue fighting until the Afghan government falls. <PERSON> Sadruddin </PERSON> left <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on Friday for <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, where he will talk with government leaders and refugee experts on the relief and repatriation effort. It is his first trip to the region since <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> named him to oversee the refugee return. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> will appeal in June for funds to launch the program, said <PERSON> Sadruddin </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees. But `` if the conflict continues, it will be difficult to put the structures into place,'' <PERSON> Sadruddin </PERSON> said. Land mines littering the countryside after 10 years of civil war must be removed `` before anyone can go back,'' he said. An internal <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> document compiled last month predicted it would cost about $ 130 million for 1 million refugees to return and $ 324 million for the return of 3 million refugees. About 2.4 million Afghans live in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, and another 3.1 million live in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> figures.
