<HEAD>Child Finds Poison-Laced Chocolates On Roadside</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 10-year-old girl found two pieces of poisoned chocolate on a roadside in southwestern <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> on Friday, the latest in a series of poisoned candy incidents since September. <PERSON> Hideyoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Bando </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Tokushima </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prefectural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>, said the child, who did not eat the candy, found it on her way to school near the town of <LOCATION> Itano </LOCATION>. She reported it to a teacher, who notified police. <PERSON> Bando </PERSON> said preliminary tests on the chocolate indicated the presence of a highly poisonous acid. The incident was the second such case in two months in the <LOCATION> Tokushima </LOCATION> region, 320 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Three pieces of poisoned chocolate were found April 3 in the grass near a religious shrine in the area. Chocolates tainted with poison were first discovered in two schools in neighboring <LOCATION> Kagawa </LOCATION> region on Sept. 8, 1987, and similar incidents were reported the same month in at least three other <LOCATION> Tokushima </LOCATION> schools. Police suspect the same person or group is responsible for the string of incidents.
