<FIRST>r i AM-MoscowAtItsBest Bjt   05-27 0875</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Moscow At Its Best, Bjt,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lilacs Blooming, Stores Stocked _ It's Moscow At Its Best</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in his first visit to the Soviet capital, will see an enormous city of 12-lane boulevards dominated in part by seven massive Stalin-era Baroque buildings. He will see the city at its best: the lilacs are blooming, the weather is mild and downtown stores are stocked with meat and tomatoes. Arriving for the first time in the Soviet capital is at times like taking a trip back in time. The electrical appliances seem old-fashioned and traffic jams are rare, though smog has taken hold. Nearly 9 million people live here, yet the only time it seems crowded is when people are queuing to buy food, perfume, and other scarce consumer goods. Humans are dwarfed by immense buildings, both the charmless, modern structures from the 1960s _ said to be modeled on buildings <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> saw and liked in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> _ and a variety of monuments to mother <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>'s war heroes. Few of the cars are new, almost all are Soviet-made, and taxicabs seem scarce, at least to the legion of visitors who arrived this week to prepare for the Reagan-Gorbachev summit. Most Muscovites do not own cars, and so while <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and Politburo members are whisked into the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> during the morning rush hour and out again at dusk, millions of commuters use the city's excellent subway or local bus and trolley systems. The Kremlin is not one big building, like the Pentagon for example. Instead, it is a walled citadel of government buildings, cathedrals, towers and arsenals dating back to the 14th Century. `` <LOCATION> Alcatraz </LOCATION> on the outside, <LOCATION> Versailles </LOCATION> on the inside,'' in the words of one American. Some of the city's best known sites _ the red-and-white and yellow-and-blue onion domes of St. Basil's Cathedral, cobblestoned Red Square and the Bolshoi Theater _ sit just outside the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> ` s red-brick wall. The words `` grim,'' `` drab,'' `` dreary,' and `` unkempt'' are often used to describe <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, but the sunny skies _ the first in 10 months _ the sweet-smelling purple lilacs and the pre-summit spruce-up helps overcome the feeling of grayness brought on in large part by decades of listless architecture. `` It's not <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, but it's a lot prettier that it was two months ago,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. Soldiers, in their gray tunics and green hats, are shining the huge swinging metal doors on government buildings. Women on hands and knees are planting begonias in front of the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> wall, workers are mowing the grass sprinkled with yellow dandelions and plasterers are touching up the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, where <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will visit A three-man team is painting the flagpoles of the <LOCATION> Pushkin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION>. Residents seem excited about the upcoming <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> visit. At the Hotel Rossiya, home to many of the American journalists and officials working at the summit, the local employees _ not widely known for wasting pleasantries _ are going out of their way to be helpful. The dezhurni, Russian `` key ladies'' who are posted day and night on each hotel floor _ smile when you turn in the key after leaving the room. Service may be slow, but this week at least it is service with a smile. `` Service is impossible here,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, a businessman from <LOCATION> Basking </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, who has dealt with the Soviets in his advertising business. `` There's no motivation, that's the problem,'' he said. Black and his wife, <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON>, say they have deep affection for the Soviet people. `` When you get to know them, they are very nice,'' he said. For Americans, the language barrier is a real problem, he said, because the Soviets may seem rude when they are really just embarrassed at not being able to communicate. While Soviet bureaucrats and law enforcement officials generally wear a dour expression, young people were smiling as they strolled in the May sunshine along the broad sidewalks of <LOCATION> Kalinin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prospekt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s `` Fifth Avenue,'' where behind the glass shop windows are a paltry number of fashions and consumer products. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has little street crime, no doubt partly a result of the omnipresence of police. There are so many uniformed officers that they sometimes seem to be watching one another. The <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> militia says none of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s 60 banks has been robbed in 20 years. The hotels have plenty of food on hand for the summit, attracting large numbers of Soviets who filled their bellies, and in some cases their pockets, with such rarities as tomatoes, sausages and cheese _ items that the locals say have not been seen for weeks in most stores. The beriozkas, special hotel shops which accept only Western currency, are freshly stocked for the summit, and foreign residents of the city have been seen carting cases of wine to their waiting cars _ a basic precaution in a society where such commodities may not reappear for months. <PERSON> Renee </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>, a teacher from <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, said her biggest disappointment on her trip to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is that the facilities are `` dirty and unhygienic.'' But that hardly affected her trip, she said. `` The people are so nice and they love Americans,'' she said.
</TEXT>
