e to change their minds, but they ca n't ever say they were n't informed.'' <PERSON> Vickers </PERSON> said that the county commissioners in 1983 agreed to let <PERSON> DiMaio </PERSON> do work for the <ORGANIZATION> Bone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> and decided the county would bill the foundation $ 25 per case for use of the facilities, <PERSON> Vickers </PERSON> said. `` It was all above board,'' <PERSON> Vickers </PERSON> said. `` As far as I can tell, he did n't try to hide anything. His statement was given in open court, in front of attorneys and auditors.'' <PERSON> DiMaio </PERSON> likened his role to a physician removing a heart from an accident victim for use in another transplant. `` Everyone is paid for their services,'' he said. At the foundation, the bones are cleaned and chopped into pieces and freeze-dried for use in transplants, mostly for back, dental or reconstructive surgery.
