<FIRST>r a AM-Out-Of-BodyLivers     05-27 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Out-Of-Body Livers,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surgeon Repairs Livers Outside Body</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hoping to buy time for victims of one of the bleakest forms of cancer, a West German surgeon is repairing livers outside the body, a procedure believed to be the first of its kind. `` I think it may help some patients for whom we could n't do anything else,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Rudolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hannover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> said that he has removed, repaired and replaced livers three times, including twice this month. Malignant liver tumors left no choice, he said. The repairs took four to five hours. The patients, two women and a man, were doing well, <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> said Thursday by telephone from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` They are improved dramatically,'' he said. `` I'm afraid those patients might get a reoccurrence of the disease. But I feel the justification to do it because it's the best possible retaliation'' against cancer. He said that because of the nature of liver cancer, the patients would probably eventually develop new tumors, either in the liver or elsewhere, but the operation at least will prolong their lives. Previously, such bench surgery was limited to the well-established repair of blood vessels or the removal of cysts and tumors in kidneys, which are less delicate and less vital to sustaining life than the liver. `` It's a very intriguing development,'' said liver transplant pioneer Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Starzl </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION>. `` I can see how it might be a significant advance, although we really must wait and see,'' he said. `` My hat's off to him. It's a monumental effort,'' said liver transplant surgeon Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Najarian </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>. He has tried liver transplants on four liver cancer patients, only one of whom is still alive. Liver cancer is among the deadlier forms of the disease, said <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahaney </PERSON>. Early detection gives patients a 10 percent to 30 percent chance of surviving for five years. Late detection leaves a mere 3 percent chance. <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> performed the first operation Feb. 5 to remove cancer that more than doubled the weight of a 40-year-old woman's liver. The woman has since returned home. He said a transplant might have wasted a valuable donor organ because the cancer had spread beyond her liver, and he avoided traditional in-body repairs because of the tumor's size and central location. As he removed the organ, <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> installed a pump that kept blood flowing through the two main explosed blood vessels. Outside the body, the liver was cooled with ice water and flushed periodically with a special fluid to keep it fresh. <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> described the procedure in a West German medical journal in April. `` She's gained weight again, and at this moment she's very healthy,'' he said. `` She was suffering extremely, and I think she would not be alive now.'' <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> performed liver bench surgery again May 6 on a 48-year-old woman and May 11 on a 58-year-old man. `` The lady is at home, quite well,'' he said. `` The man is still in the hospital, but is good.'' Also this year, <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> did the world's first split-liver transplant, dividing one liver and implanting the halves into two patients.
</TEXT>
