<HEAD>Sikhs Kill Seven; Security Corridor To Be Built Around Golden
Temple</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sikh terrorists killed seven people Friday in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state, and two people died of injuries suffered in an earlier bomb blast. The government announced plans to shut off the Golden Temple to militant Sikhs. Home Minister <PERSON> Buta </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, whose ministry is responsible for internal security, told reporters the government would carve out a 100-yard corridor around the temple complex to try to keep extremists from using the shrine as a hideout. The office of President <PERSON> Ramaswami </PERSON> <PERSON> Venkataraman </PERSON> announced that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 30-year-old Arms Act had been amended to provide stringent punishment for the use of outlawed firearms. Under the amendment, a person convicted of possessing prohibited arms such as rocket launchers could be sentenced to life in prison. The government says Sikh extremists are bringing these more sophisticated arms in from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Previously, the maximum sentence was three years in prison. The moves came one day after the president issued an ordinance making it illegal for temples and other religious sites to be used for political purposes. The ordinance also would make harboring a wanted criminal in a shrine punishable by imprisonment or a fine. Two of the people who died Friday were Hindu laborers injured Thursday when a bomb went off in a crowded market in the town of <LOCATION> Phagwara </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Kapurthala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> east of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. The bombing was blamed on the <PERSON> Barbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalsa </PERSON> gang, one of a dozen Sikh extremist groups operating in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. It was the latest in a series of attacks on migrant workers. Police believe the extremists are trying to drive Hindu laborers out of the state and undercut its agricultural economy. Seven other deaths were reported Friday, including a Sikh father and