<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five old trucks and buses, driven by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> veterans, left the capital Friday as part of the nationwide `` Veterans Peace Convoy'' bearing food, medical supplies, clothing and toys for the children of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The contingent will merge June 5 in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, with several other conveys that originated in northern cities a week ago. Then the entire group, involving 50 vehicles and 100 drivers, will begin the drive through <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Livesay </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Dorchester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, veteran who hatched the project and heads the group that started in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, said a total of about 40 tons of humanitarian aid will be delivered by the convoy to private relief agencies in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. `` This is a people-to-people project to feed children, not a government one to feed war,'' <PERSON> Livesay </PERSON> said. The veterans' drive also is designed to promote the larger `` Let <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> Live'' program, under which various peace groups plan to send 4,200 tons of oats to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> via container ships this year. The various legs of the convoy will pass through 40 states, with stops in 90 cities, <PERSON> Livesay </PERSON> said. Other groups started in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>;, <LOCATION> Missoula </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mont </PERSON>.; <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, Ore. Among the donated supplies driven by the veterans are hospital equipment, powdered milk, and oral rehydration salts to help battle diarrhea, the No. 1 cause of death among Nicaraguan infants. The trucks also will carry stuffed animals and baseball equipment for the children. <PERSON> Livesay </PERSON> said he got the idea for the drive during a trip to northern <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> last fall on behalf of the Veterans for Peace. When another veteran mentioned the possibility of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion aimed at <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist government, he said, `` Something clicked. I said he ought to invade this place ourselves with a convoy of real humanitarian aid.'' <PERSON> Livesay </PERSON> said, `` The kids were saw were malnourished, with discolored hair and distended stomachs, without clothes. The war had really begun to destroy the ability of the people in the countryside to produce.'' `` I saw the situation developing the same way it did in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Livesay </PERSON>, who worked for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> security branch in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> in the 1960s. `` I could n't believe that after 20 years, we just had n't learned our lesson.'' He said the relief materials will be handed over to non-governmental social service agencies in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, including the Institute of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> XXIII </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>.
