<FIRST>r a AM-Pregnancy-Drugs     05-27 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pregnancy-Drugs,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Best Advice for Drugs in Pregnancy: Ask A Doctor
^With AM-Accutane Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The best way to avoid harmful drugs during pregnancy is to refrain from all medications, except those specifically approved by your doctor for use during your pregnancy, medical authorities say. In addition, consumers can learn about pregnancy-related risks of a drug by asking a pharmacist to see the labeling, or by checking the pharmacist's copy of the Physicians' Desk Reference. Here is a partial list of drugs other than Accutane that experts recommend avoiding during pregnancy, or which should be taken only with approval of a physician: - Aspirin. - Blood-thinning drugs derived from a substance called coumarin. They are taken for heart-related disorders. - Cancer drugs that are cytotoxic, which means they kill cells. - Drugs containing any male or female hormone such as estrogens, progesterone or anabolic steroids. - Some anticonvulsants; a physician can prescribe lower-risk ones. - Cough syrup with a large percentage of alcohol. - Minor tranquilizers such as Valium or <LOCATION> Librium </LOCATION>. - Etretinate, used for severe psoriasis. - Vitamins A or B. In large doses they are linked to birth defects.
</TEXT>
