<HEAD>Riot Police Roughly Break Up Anti-Government Protests
^LaserPhoto SEL3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Riot police kicked and clubbed anti-government protesters Friday and fired tear gas grenades after President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON> ordered that all measures be taken to crush violent demonstrations. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>, presiding over a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, said the dissident protests threaten the safety of the Olympic Games, which begin Sept. 17 in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. As part of tightened security preceding the Games, a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister ordered police to maintain surveillance on foreigners spending long periods of time in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> without a definite purpose. In downtown <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, angry passers-by shouted `` Shame!'' as some of an estimated 7,000 riot police fired tear gas and repeatedly charged about 3,000 radical students. Police chased protesters into subways and tossed tear gas grenades at passers-by who protested. Several officers lifted a protesting businessman in a blue suit above their heads and carried him away. Police broke up an attempted sit-in at City Hall and an attempt by about 500 students to march toward the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> library. They arrested dozens of students, beating and kicking many of the protesters and hitting them with clubs as they were dragged away. There were no reports of injuries, and police did not give an overall arrest figure. Some students hurled firebombs and rocks at police, but most just chanted anti-government and anti-U.S. slogans. `` Down with the military dictatorship!'' `` Punish <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo!'' and `` Drive out the <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION>!'' they yelled. Radical students claim the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> supports military rule in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and enforces partition of the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> peninsula </LOCATION>, divided since 1945. The protesters demand the expulsion of the 42,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops based in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Protesters have attacked <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomatic buildings during the protests, including the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. No Americans have been hurt. Protesters have also demanded that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> serve as co-hosts of the Olympics as a move toward reunification of the two countries. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> called the radicals a threat to the safety of the Games and said, `` It is imperative that all possible measures be taken to forestall acts of violence by domestic radical groups.'' <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> also warned that <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> `` may stage any kind of adventure and provocation to mar the success of the Games.'' Home Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Choon-koo </PERSON>, who is in charge of the nation's 135,000 police, ordered the watch on certain foreigners to prevent infiltration by terrorists at the Olympics The government inaugurated a 13,000-member police <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> to guard Olympic athletes and facilities. Members were selected for martial arts and foreign language skills. Police also distributed 5,000 leaflets nationwide with portraits of seven people suspected in the hijacking in 1970 of a Japanese jetliner to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> by the terrorist <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> group. One person suspected in the hijacking, <PERSON> Yasuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Shibata </PERSON>, 34, was arrested in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> after returning from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> on a false passport, police said. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, a police spokesman said officers were questioning <PERSON> Shibata </PERSON> to try to determine if the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> planned any renewed terrorist action. In the southern city of <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION>, about 5,000 people marched peacefully to mark the anniversary of the end of a 1980 anti-government uprising in which at least 191 people died. A memorial service was held in <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION>, about 165 miles south of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. Afterward, marchers, with a coffin bearing pictures of the dead, walked through the city. Radicals claim <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>, an army general at the time, helped direct the police action.
