<HEAD>Pleads Guilty in Iran Radio Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The owner of an electronics company has pleaded guilty to conspiring to ship military radios to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowitz </PERSON> agreed to the plea in an arrangement with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office Thursday. A 1985 federal indictment charged that <ORGANIZATION> Bowitz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> promised to sell up to 6,000 radios to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> through two Iranian agents operating out of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. The radios were the type used by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bowitz </PERSON> also pleaded guilty on behalf of his company to a charge of planning to illegally export $ 300,000 in listening devices to <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>. His wife, <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON>, agreed to plead guilty to illegal possession of a machine gun and to a charge of planning the illegal export of radios to <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. The couple and their company face potential fines and restitution payments of at least $ 4.6 million, according to court documents. The crimes also carry maximum five-year prison terms, but the government stipulated that prison sentences be suspended. Under the plea bargain, <PERSON> Bowitz </PERSON> has agreed to leave the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> within six months of his sentencing, scheduled June 29.
