<FIRST>r a AM-WaterWoes     05-27 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Water Woes,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Don't Drink the Water,' Schools Tell Students</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Students in a rural <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> school district and in eight <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> schools were told, `` Do n't drink the water,'' after potentially hazardous matter was found in their drinking supplies. The order to stop using the water at <LOCATION> Snow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> <LOCATION> School </LOCATION>, about 40 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, came Thursday on the last day of class. The <ORGANIZATION> Alabama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, which tested the water earlier this month, found that its coliform bacteria count was more than 25 times the level considered potentially dangerous. Coliform bacteria are normally found in animals' colon; in water supplies, they indicate contamination by fecal matter. Continued high exposure to the bacteria make a person more susceptible to digestive disorders, said <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamar </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the environmental agency. In <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, the problem was excessive amounts of lead, discovered in the water supplies of eight public schools in a television station's survey. The report prompted testing at all city schools over the Memorial Day weekend, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Stobierski </PERSON> of the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. `` These schools that have high levels of lead or those that we do n't have results for will be on bottled water when schools reopen on Tuesday, after the holiday,'' <PERSON> Stobierski </PERSON> said. The drinking water at <ORGANIZATION> Snow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> was `` as bad as you can get,'' said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Power </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> ADEM </ORGANIZATION>'s public water supply branch. `` It's like drinking untreated water from a creek or river.'' <PERSON> Power </PERSON> said samples taken by his agency May 16 showed the water to be contaminated at more than 25 times the potentially dangerous level of coliform bacteria. School systems in the state are supposed to test their water monthly and report bacterial levels to the state, and the agency stepped in when it failed to receive the reports from the district. He said students at Snow Hill have been drinking well water contaminated at more than seven times the danger level since January, when the school reopened after being shut for 15 years. The 347 students were switched to Snow Hill from a school in <LOCATION> Pine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> after state officials ordered the county not to use the <LOCATION> Pine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> school, which was plagued by leakage of raw sewage and other problems. A fire destroyed the main campus building at <LOCATION> Pine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> last fall. <PERSON> Power </PERSON> said stomach aches, viruses or other illness contracted by students since January possibly could have been caused by the drinking water. The district's superintendent, <PERSON> Odell </PERSON> <PERSON> Tumblin </PERSON>, said she does not believe the problem is as serious as <ORGANIZATION> ADEM </ORGANIZATION> indicates. `` That water is clear and pure and a lot of families in the area have been using the same well for years,'' she said. `` I do n't see how the water system got poisoned just because the students got there.'' A new high school is being built in <LOCATION> Camden </LOCATION>, but school officials plan to use <LOCATION> Snow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> at least another year. <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s WNEV-TV had water samples from 24 elementary schools analyzed and discovered that 10, including two private schools, had lead levels exceeding federal standards. <PERSON> Stobierski </PERSON> said the tainted water was unlikely to cause acute lead poisoning, but said scientists still do n't fully understand the chronic effects of low-level lead poisoning.
</TEXT>
