<HEAD>Soviet Protests US Arms Shipments to Afghan Guerrillas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs 7th graf bgng, (In Washington) with 2 new grafs
giving State Department reaction.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An adviser to Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said Friday that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is violating a peace accord by continuing to ship arms to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s anti-communist <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas. `` They are arming, quite openly, those who want to go on in their civil war,'' said <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Primakov </PERSON>, who has advised <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> on arranging the Soviet troop withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Primakov </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economy </ORGANIZATION> and International Relations, did not specify when the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> sent its most recent arms shipment to the Mujahedeen. No did he say whether continued <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shipments might halt withdrawal of the estimated 105,500 Soviet troops who are still in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. `` This means that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will jeopardize the situation,'' <PERSON> Primakov </PERSON> told a news conference for reporters covering next week's summit talks between <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. `` It means they will push <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> into a corner,'' he said. `` It destroys the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords.'' -LRB- In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Justesen </PERSON> said in response to <PERSON> Primakov </PERSON>'s charges: -LRB- `` The turnover of large amounts of military supplies constitutes a continuation of military aid. The Soviets should take their military equipment out with them. We will watch Soviet actions in this area carefully and will follow symmetry in making our decisions.'' Marshal <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Akhromeyev </PERSON>, chief of staff of the Soviet armed forces, told reporters Thursday that 9,500 of his troops have left <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> since the pullout began May 15. Under the peace accord, the Soviet withdrawal is supposed to be completed by early 1989. <PERSON> Primakov </PERSON>'s charge appeared to be part of a pattern of protests aimed at pressuring <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to stop aiding the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION>. On Thursday, the Afghan government lodged its fourth protest with a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> observer mission, accusing <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> of continuing to channel arms to the guerrillas. The guerrillas have said they will continue to fight the Soviet-backed government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and will ignore the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords signed by <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> regime. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> agreed to act as guarantors of the agreement. In an exchange of letters, each side agreed to stop arming its allies in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> if the other followed suit. The letters, which have not been made public, also are reported to have specified that if either side continued to arm its Afghan ally, the other would provide a commensurate level of weapons to its side. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has halted its arms shipments, Western diplomats say, but is leaving Soviet military bases and massive arms supplies to the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government as its forces pull out. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been supplying the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> with an estimated $ 500 million annually in arms and military supplies channeled through <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. About 2.5 million Afghans have fled to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> since the Soviets invaded <LOCATION> Afganistan </LOCATION> in December 1979, and the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> operate out of basis on Pakistani soil. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> also have supplied arms to the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> but have not signed the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords. An additional 1.5 million Afghan refugees are living in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which is supporting Islamic fundamentalist guerrilla groups.
