<HEAD>Lawmakers Divided On Reimposing Martial Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Old-guard lawmakers from the governing <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> called for the return of martial law Friday after violent protests that injured hundreds of people, but their younger colleagues denounced the idea. Martial law was lifted in July after 38 years in force. Last Friday and Saturday, riot police and demonstrators battled in <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> for 18 hours, and there has been talk the government might bring back martial law. More than 200 people reportedly were injured and 96 protesters were detained in the riots, which broke out after a farmers' rights demonstration. The violence was the worst on this island since 1947, when native Taiwanese staged an uprising against <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> forces who had arrived from the Chinese mainland. A group of 75 legislators issued a statement calling the recent rioting `` a bloody incident unprecedented in 40 years.'' They urged the government to partially reimpose martial law because the nation had reached `` the moment of life and death.'' The statement said violent protests threatened national security and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s economic development. Most members of the Legislative Yuan who signed the statement were elected on mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> shortly before 1949, when they and the rest of the Nationalist government fled to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> after losing a civil war to the Communists. The Nationalist government claims to be the rightful ruler of all <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. A group of 27 lawmakers comprised mostly of Nationalist legislators elected in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> issued a statement opposed to a return to martial law and said it would drive `` the vehicle of democracy backward.'' The rioting was a temporary disorder and the government should not easily give up its achievement in democracy, the statement said. Since the lifting of martial law, under which demonstrations were banned, protests have been held almost daily by dissidents and other groups pressing a wide variety of political and economic demands. Newspapers reported Thursday that members of the party's policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> held heated discussions at a weekly meeting Wednesday about whether the government should reimpose martial law <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> police, meanwhile, turned down an application by a farmer's group to march in <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> on Tuesday, claiming the organization violated demonstration laws during previous protests. <PERSON> Lin </PERSON> <PERSON> Feng-hsi </PERSON>, spokesman of the group, said the farmers wanted to march to apologize to <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> residents for last week's violent protest. Also Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> announced that three sons of the late President <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-kuo </PERSON> were elected delegates to the <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> congress this summer. <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON>, who died in January, was the son of <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Kai-shek </PERSON>, who led the Nationalists to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> in 1949. He was the main architect of the recent policies of easing the Nationalists' authoritarian grip on <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and allowing unofficial contacts with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.
