<HEAD>Algae Killing Tons Of Fish In Scandinavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 300-mile carpet of algae along the southern coast of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> has killed tons of salmon and rainbow trout, a <LOCATION> Norweigan </LOCATION> newspaper reported Friday. The single-cell algae has killed all marine life down to a depth of 26 feet in some parts of <LOCATION> Skagerrak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> between <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and in the <LOCATION> Kattegat </LOCATION> belt between <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION> daily Aftenposten said. <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, alarmed by weather reports showing the algae could be blown to its shores, dispatched a research boat Friday to track the growth. `` I've never experienced anything like it. The situation is highly dramatic,'' <PERSON> Arne </PERSON> <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON>, head of the Sea Pollution Laboratory of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, said Friday. <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON> blamed nitrates and phosphorus washed into the sea from farms. Authorities say the algae is not harmful to humans, but it turns to slime on the gills of fish and chokes them to death. The algae growth extends about 310 miles along the southwest coast of <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Goteborg </LOCATION> to the oil center of <LOCATION> Stavanger </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. Wild fish such as herring and flounder have not been as hard hit as the trout and salmon grown by Norwegian farmers in seaside pens, experts said. Those farmers have been advised by marine biologists to slaughter their fish. Some major fish farms in western <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> have started to tow their nets away from coastal areas into <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s deep, cool fiords to avoid the algae threat. Marine biologist <PERSON> Einar </PERSON> <PERSON> Dahl </PERSON> said it could take weeks or months for the algae to disappear, according to the newspaper. He said the algae has always been present in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> but never in such quantities.
