<HEAD>Undercover Police Veteran Arrested On Drug Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 31-year veteran undercover officer whose testimony helped convict an officer of the scandal-ridden 77th Precinct has been arrested on drug charges, authorities said. Detective <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Poulson </PERSON>, 56, of <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>, who had spent the last 13 years in the Internal Affairs Division investigating corrupt cops, was himself arrested by IAD investigators Thursday, IAD Chief <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. `` He was a very dedicated and good performer,'' the chief said. `` I'm shocked and saddened that he would give up his 30 years of police service and his pension for this brief encounter.'' In 1987, <PERSON> Poulson </PERSON> had posed as a cocaine dealer during an investigation of police corruption at the 77th Precinct, which resulted in the indictment of 13 officers. Videotapes of <PERSON> Poulson </PERSON> offering an officer a $ 500 payoff for protection helped convict the officer. A unidentified woman arrested in April on drug charges told narcotics officers <PERSON> Poulson </PERSON> had introduced her to drugs four years ago, <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. The woman contacted <PERSON> Poulson </PERSON> and he agreed to meet her Thursday night at a house police had wired for sound. Investigators said <PERSON> Poulson </PERSON> possessed slightly less than an eighth of an ounce of cocaine that he was going to give to the woman. `` There were indications he had been using drugs recently,'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. The detective refused to take a drug test on the advice of his attorney. There were no indications that <PERSON> Poulson </PERSON> had been dealing cocaine, or that he had obtained the narcotic from police seizures, the chief added. <PERSON> Poulson </PERSON> was charged with one count of drug possession and two counts of drug possession with intent to sell. The maximum penalty for the last two counts is a prison term of up to 25 years. <PERSON> Poulson </PERSON> earned about $ 50,000 a year. Under police regulations, he was eligible to retire with a pension worth two-thirds of his annual salary after 30 years.
