<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> received encouragement from on high Friday for their summit talks next week. `` We as people hope that the summit brings peace,'' cosmonaut <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Titov </PERSON> said in a live television interview as he orbited <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> in the Soviet space station Mir, which means `` peace'' in Russian. A group of reporters in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> asked <PERSON> Titov </PERSON> and fellow cosmonaut <PERSON> Musa </PERSON> <PERSON> Manarov </PERSON> about <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s comment in a recent interview with <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> that he will ask <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to support a joint U.S.-Soviet mission to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>. `` As for joint scientific projects, our country has always been for them. We confirm that,'' said <PERSON> Titov </PERSON>, who wore a gray-blue flight suit. He predicted that a manned expedition to Mars could be carried out within 10 years. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> did not specify whether he was proposing a manned or unmanned flight to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>. Other Soviet officials said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> envisioned an unmanned mission. <PERSON> Titov </PERSON>, 41, who is from the Siberian town of <LOCATION> Sretensk </LOCATION>, has been aboard the Mir spacecraft as commander since December. Mir was launched in February 1986 as a permanent manned space station, and cosmonauts have been conducting scientific and medical experiments on board since it soared into orbit. <PERSON> Titov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Manarov </PERSON>, a 37-year-old member of the tiny Soviet ethnic group called the Lakets, spoke by television to reporters who toured the Soviet mi