<HEAD>Iranian Gunboats Hit Maltese Ship in Fourth Recent Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Iran-Iraq, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX MINASIAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Iranian gunboats attacked a Maltese freighter and set it ablaze Friday in the <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>. It was <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s fourth raid in 10 days on ships sailing to or from Saudi ports. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> apparently was retaliating for a spate of Iraqi raids on its oil - shipping lanes, including one attack that devastated five tankers May 14 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> targets vessels trading with <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> because it accuses the two oil-rich powers of aiding <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, its enemy in the 7 -LCB- - year-old <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war The 18,000-ton <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> was left burning fiercely after the morning attack in the <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>, the gateway to the gulf. The 18-member South Korean crew abandoned the vessel, shipping executives said. The executives, speaking on condition of anonymity, also said the Iranians fired at a helicopter chartered by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> television network <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> when it approached the site of the attack. The aircraft was not hit. The shipping officials said they were not aware of any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships, which patrol the gulf to protect shipping, near where the Iranians struck. In the past 10 days, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has attacked three other foreign ships. The <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> was hit about 12 hours after the Norwegian-operated Mundogas Rio was attacked in the same area, about 25 miles south of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s Larak island oil terminal. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> turned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION