<HEAD>Nixon Says Post-Convention Summit Would Be `Three-Ring Circus'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit-Reagan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> says a proposed fifth Reagan-Gorbachev summit after the Democratic and Republican conventions this summer would be meaningless unless both parties' presidential candidates also agree to attend Such a meeting, <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> said, `` would be a ludicrous three-ring circus.'' President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> held out the possibility of yet another summit before he departed Wednesday for summit talks with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> next week. The German newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Die </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welt </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as saying the Soviets are interested in concluding a Strategic Arms Reduction Talks or START treaty with him, rather than waiting until his successor takes over in January. <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> said that with only five months remaining before the Nov. 8 presidential election, too little time remains for the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to complete an arms control agreement that would be in the national interest. `` Once the two major parties choose their tickets for the general election, an incumbent's authority _ in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> eyes _ drops to nil,'' he said. `` Any summit after the two conventions will be meaningless unless both the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> and Democratic nominees agreed to attend. In the unlikely event that they did, it would be a ludicrous three-ring circus.'' <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s views are contained in a column he wrote for this weekend's editions of the Sunday Times of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. A copy was obtained by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, who had three summit meetings with Soviet leaders while he was president, said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> does n't have enough time left as president to resolve several important Soviet-American issues. Among them, he said, are the relationship between defensive and offensive weapons systems, whether to allow mobile strategic missiles, and verification of cruise and mobile missiles. Therefore, <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> said, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> should concentrate in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on conventional arms control and regional political conflicts. Trying to rush the START talks toward settlement `` would put the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the intolerable position of negotiating against a deadline in questions that directly affect our survival,'' <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> said. Even signing a draft agreement would be a mistake, he said. `` That would lock the next administration into an approach that focused excessively on cuts in the number of nuclear weapons instead of the critical issue: the stability of the strategic balance,'' he wrote. <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> said the centerpiece of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> approach should be conventional arms control in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and not any goal of making equal cutbacks in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` While American forces would retreat to the other side of an ocean, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s forces would simply take a short train ride to the western border of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` Instead, we should seek asymetrical reductions in the Kremlin's armies.'' The former president said progress on U.S.-Soviet economic cooperation must be linked to resolving regional disputes in which <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s actions threaten American interests, `` if we want <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to take our positions on these issues seriously.'' `` If we do not insist on linkage at the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit, we will end up subsidizing our own destruction,'' he said.
