<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Party     05-27 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Party,0732</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Reforms Outlined, But Economic Change Unclear</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Communist Party has outlined a series of reforms that could sweep away many political and judicial remnants of Stalinism. But it has failed to say how it will transform the economy. The changes are sketched in a program that will be debated next month at a party conference considered crucial to the future of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms. The document, published in Soviet newspapers Friday, was approved at a <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meeting this week and stresses the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s need to modernize all aspects of society. It speaks of elections for some posts, of reducing some adminstrative powers of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, of limiting the terms of office and of democratic reforms. While the proposal makes no concessions to demands for a multi-party system, it says social organizations that are not limited to <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members should have `` a bigger say in the political process in future.'' The nation's laws will be reviewed, the document says, and `` We must firmly adhere to the following principle: Everything is permissible unless prohibited by the law.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has stressed reforms of the judicial and political system as crucial to ending the vestiges of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s dictatorship. But even if the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference approves all the changes, their implementation may be slowed by resistance in some quarters. Changes envisaged in the political system include a limit of two five-year terms for for party and government officials all the way up to the policy-setting <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the Supreme Soviet, the nation's parliament. The party also is ordered to keep hands off day-to-day management of the economy and government, and concentrate on setting goals. Almost all the proposed changes, called the `` theses'' for the party conference opening June 28, had been raised before by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> or his followers. But in an apparent victory for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the principle of secret ballot elections for some posts was adopted. The party leader also appears to have gained a chance to sweep opponents from positions of influence. The conference will consider calling for a review of all the party's 19 million members. The review is likely to focus on the clear struggle between orthodox Communists used to the authoritarian party system set up by <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and reformers who want to see <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms succeed. The theses contained strong criticism of what it said was the abuse of power under the system built up by <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, and of the political and economic stagnation that set in under <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, who was in power from 1964 to 1982. It declared the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was `` on the brink of an economic crisis'' after <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>. Although progress has been made, the program said the economy still is far from the modern financial and monetary system <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> wants. An economist close to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aganbegyan </PERSON>, told reporters Friday that despite three years of reform efforts, most average Soviets have seen no improvement in their lives. He said a reform of prices, which is promised for the early 1990s, is essential. <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Shmelev </PERSON>, an economist known for his controversial proposals, said the Soviet economy suffers from gross inefficiency. It has a shortage of 20 million workers in some sectors, but 25 million extra workers in other sectors, he said. In apparent deference to growing grumbling among consumer about shortages, the theses also stressed that supplies of food and consumer goods must be sharply increased. Scientists and educators were castigated for not doing enough to introduce new technology and new thinking, but the biggest criticism was reserved for managers and bureaucrats who still want to boss others around. The only sector of the population praised for its contribution to the reform effort was the intelligentsia, who have proved the most vocal supporters of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms. That reflects in part changes that have given Soviets more interesting newspapers, livelier television programs and some previously banned films, books and music. If the document is accepted by the 5,000 delegates to the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference, it will mark an important consolidation of reforms to date for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and give him the basis to go further in transforming the Stalinist system he inherited.
