<HEAD>Main Points of Soviet Party Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are the main points of <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> proposals published in Friday's Soviet newspapers: _ On political pluralism The paper says `` a salient feature of our time is the appearance of a real pluralism of opinions, open comparison of ideas and interests.'' It does not envisage abandonment of the one-party system, but suggests that some social organizations outside the party should have a bigger say in the political process in future _ Local and regional legislatures and the national <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> are to play an enhanced role in political debate and to operate under legal guarantees that their decisions will not be undone by bureaucratic interference _ The legal system is to be strengthened, presuming the innocence of those on trial and radically reforming the operation of state prosecutors Soviet laws are to be rewritten and the principle adopted that `` everything is permissible unless prohibited by the law.'' _ Reforms should allow for the exercise of constitutional freedoms _ freedom of press, conscience, assembly, street demonstrations and `` firmer guarantees of personal rights, such as the inviolability of the person and the home, and privacy of correspondence and telephone conversations, to name but a few. _ Party and government officials should be limited to two five-year terms in office, with third terms permissible only by majority vote in secret ballot of party and government offices concerned The proposals say this practice should extend all the way to the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and to the Supreme Soviet, or national parliament. _ Due attention should be paid to ethnic relations, and political institutions formed to articulate ethnic interests made `` more active. _ The party should be reformed to prevent a repeat of the abuses of power developed under <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and `` those who in the past fell victim to unjustified political accusations and illegality'' should be rehabilitated
