<HEAD>White Apartheid Opponent Concludes Talks With ANC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s best-known white apartheid opponents met Friday with representatives of an outlawed black guerrilla movement but said the two sides formed no concrete agreements about reforming their country. <PERSON> Frederik </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Zyl </PERSON> <PERSON> Slabbert </PERSON>, former head of the <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, met with four national executive committee members of the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, including information and publicity head <PERSON> Thabo </PERSON> <PERSON> Mbeki </PERSON>. Among the topics discussed was the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>'s use of violence to bring about reform in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The two sides met in a <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> hotel. The <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Lusaka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>, wages a bombing and sabotage campaign to oust <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s white-led government. `` No resolutions were adopted, and no decisions were taken'' with the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> on that issue, <PERSON> Slabbert </PERSON> said, but he said the discussions were `` frank and open.'' `` I certainly do not condone bomb attacks or violence or tactics of terror of any kind,'' he added. <PERSON> Slabbert </PERSON> said the two sides discussed a broad range of issues. `` This would be a totally impossible situation in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, that you can have this kind of discussion,'' he said. `` The image of the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> amongst whites has been demonized ... by the state and its propaganda.'' <PERSON> Slabbert </PERSON>, director of an anti-apartheid think tank, said he hoped such discussions with the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> and other groups would help start a process of dialogue and debate. `` We would be happy to facilitate further discussions of this kind,'' <PERSON> Slabbert </PERSON> said, speaking on behalf of his organization, the Institute for a Democratic Alternative. <PERSON> Slabbert </PERSON> said he was finished with his current round of talks with the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> and that he would fly to <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION> on Saturday for other business. The four <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> delegates met Thursday with an eight-member delegation headed by <PERSON> Wynand </PERSON> <PERSON> Malan </PERSON>, a parliamentary member and head of the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>. As they met, two bombs exploded in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> and injured four people. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s law and order minister blamed the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> for the blasts. Five delegates from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> attended Friday's meeting between the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Slabbert </PERSON> as observers, movement delegate <PERSON> Harald </PERSON> <PERSON> Pakendorf </PERSON> told reporters. <PERSON> Slabbert </PERSON> resigned from <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in 1986, saying the body had become irrelevant and incapable of solving <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s racial problems. Last July, <PERSON> Slabbert </PERSON> led a group of about 50 South African whites for three days of talks with the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dakar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>. Those talks were widely condemned by the South African government and right-wing groups, who portray the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> as a terrorist organization and oppose all contacts with the group. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
