draperies and crystal chandeliers. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also was asked about reports that the Soviets were blocking various dissidents from attending a planned meeting with him in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Monday. He looked quizzically at Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, seated to his right, and replied, `` We do the best we can.'' White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has received assurances from the Soviets they will not block dissidents and `` refuseniks'' from attending the meeting. `` The event is on as scheduled and the people we wanted there will be there,'' he added. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the guests were picked because `` they represent the problem that he -LRB- <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> -RRB- is trying to dramatize.'' As for the reports that some people were being stopped from attending, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, `` We're trying to ascertain the facts and have made an inquiry of the Soviets.'' Underscoring the sensitivity of the topic, Jewish groups gathered in the Finnish capital to mount public pressure on <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in behalf of Soviet Jews waiting for exit permits and those seeking wider latitude to teach and practice their religion. In his speech, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said human rights would be `` an integral component'' of his dialogue with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. In a pre-summit briefing, Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Rozanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridgway </PERSON> said it would be `` subject No. 1.'' The fact that the superpowers were not able to reach agreement on a strategic arms treaty to be signed at the summit probably will give even more visibility to the human rights issue. Praising <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> for his `` glasnost''' and perestroika,'' <PERSON> R