<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court Friday upheld a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> decision to allow an affiliate of <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to underwrite and deal in commercial loan paper under strict limitations. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here rejected a challenge by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which contended that allowing an affiliate of a commercial bank to deal in loan securities violated the Glass-Steagall Act of 1933. But a three-judge court unanimously upheld the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to allow the <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to underwrite and deal in commercial paper provided the transactions did not exceed 5 percent of its gross revenues. The court, in an opinion by Circuit Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON>, noted that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> had approved a similar application by <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON>, joined by Judges <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Sentelle </PERSON>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> had correctly interpreted the law as allowing a bank affiliate to engage in a limited number of commercial paper transactions The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> correctly decided that the prohibition on bank affiliates `` principally engaged'' in securities transactions did not apply in this case, the court said. `` The statute permits banks to affiliate with firms that are not ` principally' engaged'' in securities transactions, <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> wrote. `` The board reasonably concluded that `` principally'' does not include a firm whose commercial paper transactions are subject to the limits included in its order.''
