<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Sanctions     05-27 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Sanctions,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tighter U.S. Sanctions Would Hurt South Africa, Business Group
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Proposed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> legislation to tighten economic sanctions against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> would hurt it more than previous boycotts, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business group said Friday. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> said limited <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sanctions imposed in 1986 carried little impact. But legislation now being considered by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` would have far-reaching negative effects on all companies operating in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and on the South African economy as a whole,'' group officials said. The chamber, which represents interests of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, opposes sanctions. Five chamber members traveled to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in April and met with congressmen and aides to lobby against additional sanctions. `` The measures now being debated dwarf anything that's been done so far,'' said <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, executive directer of the group. Both houses of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are weighing sanctions designed to protest <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s apartheid policies of racial segregation. The two similar bills would cut virtually all economic activity between the two countries. The moves would include disinvestment by all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies, whose South African investments are estimated at $ 1.1 billion. All trade would be banned, except for certain strategic minerals the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> buys from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in 1987 were about $ 1.3 billion and exports were also $ 1.3 billion. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said the South African government's February decision effectively banning 17 leading anti-apartheid organizations had put the sanctions issue `` back on the boil'' in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The limited sanctions approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 over President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto banned importation of certain goods and halted direct air links between the two countries. The chamber said <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has become `` complacent about further sanctions-disinvestment due to the fact that, in the short term, a large number of individuals and companies have benefited.'' Many American businesses that left <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> sold profitable operations to local businessmen at bargain prices. About 160 American companies have departed in the past two years, while about 155 remain. A wide range of South Africans, including some blacks and anti-apartheid whites, oppose sanctions on the grounds that blacks are most likely to suffer any economic hardships that result. Proponents of sanctions say economic pressure will speed up the government's race reforms. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
