<SECOND>AM-Heavy Water,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germans Halt Investigation of Black Market Heavy Water Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A West German prosecutor has stopped the investigation of a shipment of heavy water, a material used in nuclear weapons production, that may have been transported illegally to the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> expert and <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sources said Friday. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Milhollin </PERSON>, an American expert on the international market in heavy water, said a <LOCATION> Dusseldorf </LOCATION> prosecutor has dropped the investigation because he was convinced that documents were in order for shipment of the Norwegian-made heavy water by a West German company in 1983. `` He has decided that the water went where it was supposed to go and has halted the investigation,'' said <PERSON> Milhollin </PERSON>, who is a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> professor on leave to the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The Associated Press in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> was unable to reach the West German prosecutor for comment on the report, which was the second allegation recently that Norwegian-produced heavy water had been diverted illegally. <PERSON> Milhollin </PERSON> and a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official who spoke only on condition of anonymity said the 1983 heavy water shipment may have been diverted secretly to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> by way of the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has an interest in acquiring heavy water secretly. He said undocumented heavy water could be used secretly to produce and stockpile plutonium, which, in turn, could be used to make atomic weapons in violation of the nuclear non-proliferation treaty. <PERSON> Milhollin </PERSON> said that in 1985, a West German company attempted to hire an airline to fly undocumented heavy water to <LOCATION> Bombay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, but that the airline declined to take the shipment. Because of this history, he said, it is widely speculated that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> received the earlier secret shipment. The Indian government has denied the heavy water shipment was transported to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. Heavy water, or deuterium oxide, is used as a modulator in a nuclear reactor. It permits reactors to run on natural uranium instead of the more expensive and more tightly controlled enriched uranium fuel. A byproduct from the nuclear reactor is plutonium, the heart of nuclear bombs. On Tuesday, the Norwegian government said it also was investigating whether a 1986 shipment of heavy water to <LOCATION> Rumania </LOCATION> had been diverted improperly. <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> on Wednesday denied reports in the Hungarian news media it had sold the 12 -LCB- ton heavy water shipment to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> source said Friday that officials in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> were continuing to press for an investigation of the 1983 West German shipment. A Norwegian company, <ORGANIZATION> Norsk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hydro </ORGANIZATION>, sold the shipment to the West German concern, <PERSON> Rohstoff </PERSON> <PERSON> Einfuhr </PERSON>. Under the terms of the international nuclear non-proliferation treaty, such sales are subject to inspection and close documentation. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rumania </LOCATION> are parties to the treaty. <PERSON> Milhollin </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Norsk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hydro </ORGANIZATION> officials said they have four documents showing <PERSON> Rohstoff </PERSON> <PERSON> Einfuhr </PERSON> was buying the heavy water for shipment to <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. The documents include an export license from the Norwegian government; an import certificate from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>; an airbill from <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, which was transporting the shipment; and a sales contract between the two companies. Despite the documents, however, the shipment was flown from <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, where another 6.6 tons of cargo was added. The <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> plane then flew from <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>. It later left <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION>, but its destination was not been documented, <PERSON> Milhollin </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said. <PERSON> Milhollin </PERSON> said the West German prosecutor decided to drop his investigation after <PERSON> Rohstoff </PERSON> <PERSON> Einfuhr </PERSON> provided copies of a telegram and a letter showing the destination of the heavy water shipment had been changed from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. The West German company claims these documents were sent to <ORGANIZATION> Norsk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hydro </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. Officials at <ORGANIZATION> Norsk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hydro </ORGANIZATION>, however, claim the documents never were received and that the heavy water was shipped with the understanding that it was going <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Fifteen tons of heavy water is sufficient to produce about 13 pounds of plutonium a year. A bomb the size of the first one exploded over <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in 1945 uses about nine pounds of plutonium.
