<HEAD>NASA Inviting Industry Ideas For Using External Fuel Tanks In
Orbit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>, which expects to use and lose 40 space shuttle external fuel tanks in flights over the next five years, invited industry on Friday to come up with ideas for making productive use of the tanks in orbit. Now, they are allowed to break up in the atmosphere and fall into the ocean. The 152-foot tanks, which cost $ 25 million each, will be given away free but the user must pay for any costs not incurred under the present system of discarding them. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> wants the money up front. A <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> group, which represents 57 university research institutions, has proposed to use tanks for `` a wide variety of scientific and commercial concerns.'' The group, <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, proposes `` parking'' the exhausted tanks in orbit but <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> ruled out any such plan. The use must be stated in advance and a $ 100,000 deposit will be required before the space agency provides services or technical assistance. The external tank, about the size of a 747 jet transport, consists of two pressurized fuel tanks _ one loaded with liquid oxygen and one with liquid hydrogen. The half-million gallons of fuel are used up in the 10 minutes it takes for the shuttle to get into orbit and the tank is jettisoned just before that point. The space agency's announcement asks interested American companies and non-profit organizations to propose uses within 90 days. It is in line with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s space policy which calls for using the tanks for commercial purposes. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> plans to launch 40 shuttles through 1994. It said the exact number of tanks that could be made available will be decided flight-by-flight depending on the characteristics of the mission and the proposed use for a particular tank.
