<HEAD>Dramatic Photo Warning on Acne Drug Unlikely To Be First of Many</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An unprecedented government order to include the image of a deformed baby in packaging for the acne drug Accutane is unlikely to be followed by similar orders for other drugs with potential side-effects, analysts said Friday. On Thursday, the drug's maker, <ORGANIZATION> Hoffman-La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Nutley </LOCATION>, released a <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> letter outlining stricter warning requirements for the drug, which can cause life-threatening damage to fetuses when taken by pregnant women. Among other restrictions, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> also wants <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> to provide a consent form to be signed by physician and patient saying they understand the risks associated with the drug. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Advest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, a business research firm, said he doubted that the use of a jolting image such as a deformed baby would become widespread in the drug industry. He called the photograph a compromise between banning the drug and doing nothing, and said such a strong warning was acceptable to regulators and the company because Accutane is not a lifesaving drug. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Grigg </PERSON> said the side effects of other drugs are not as easily captured in a picture as a deformed infant, so trying to apply images to other products would be impractical. Accutane, which was put on the market in 1982, can cause missing facial features, heart problems and mental retardation in babies born to women taking it. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANI