<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet economist said Friday that <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has mishandled his anti-drunkenness campaign by emphasizing police methods instead of taking the long-range view of offering consumers a better choice of goods. <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Shmelev </PERSON> said the Soviet leader's campaign has driven drinking underground, encouraged moonshiners and deprived the government of liquor sales revenue. <PERSON> Shmelev </PERSON>, whose stinging criticisms of the Soviet economy in the literary journal Novy Mir have caused a wave of controversy, spoke to reporters at the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> and expanded on comments he made in a recent article. He said the campaign got drunks off the streets and out of the workplace. But he added, `` Unfortunately, I am afraid nothing has changed.'' `` The structure of consumption has changed. Instead of state-produced spirits they drink moonshine, they sometimes drink chemicals,'' he said. Some Soviets turned to drinking hair tonic, cologne and rubbing alcohol in a desperate search for spirits. <PERSON> Shmelev </PERSON> said a more effective but long-term way to solve the drinking problem is to improve consumer supplies `` so a man could use his ruble to buy a bottle of vodka or a good shirt.'' Soviet consumer goods are of notoriously poor quality and in short supply. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has promised to improve the lives of Soviets by improving the quantity and quality of food and consumer goods. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s anti-alcohol campaign, his first major initiative after taking power in March 1985, included raising the drinking age, shortening the hours of liquor stores and cutting liquor production. He and other officials credited the campaign with helping increase the life expectancy for Soviet men in the past two years. The Kremlin for years did not publish life expectancy figures, presumably because they were embarrassing. Complaints have been voiced in the Soviet press, however, that too many liquor stores have closed, forcing people who want to buy an occasional bottle of wine or vodka to stand in line for hours. <PERSON> Shmelev </PERSON> said alcoholism will be a `` problem for a number of generations, for a number of decades.'' An economist close to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aganbegyan </PERSON>, told reporters the anti-alcohol campaign achieved `` very impressive results'' in cutting liquor sales. But he added, `` Now moonshine is consumed in great quantities, even greater than before the anti-alcohol campaign was launched.'' <PERSON> Aganbegyan </PERSON> said the effort to convince people not to drink was poorly handled, and that sobriety societies set up across the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had not been effective.
