without bond awaiting trail.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A black Cuban refugee jailed more than two years on a murder charge despite two witnesses' testimony that the killer was white has been released, ending an ordeal he said was `` not supposed to happen in this country.'' At one point prosecutors had said they would seek the death penalty for <PERSON> Rigoberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Alberja </PERSON>, 32, indicted for first-degree murder in the 1982 shooting of a patron at an Allapattah bar during a holdup. <PERSON> Alberja </PERSON> was arrested in January 1986 on the tip of a police informant even though the bar's two owners said the killer was white and had straight hair. <PERSON> Alberja </PERSON> always maintained his innocence and refused offers to plea bargain. Earlier this month, the state finally conceded it could not prove its case, and <PERSON> Alberja </PERSON> was released. `` It's unbelievable,'' said <PERSON> Alberja </PERSON>'s public defender, <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>. `` If all you got is two witnesses saying the guy was Caucasian and you arrest a guy who is n't Caucasian, well then maybe you better think you got the wrong guy.'' <PERSON> Alberja </PERSON> said Thursday he had never been arrested before the murder case, and was stunned by the treatment he got from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` It is a great injustice,'' said <PERSON> Alberja </PERSON>. `` This happens in other countries, but it's not supposed to happen in this country.'' <PERSON> Alberja </PERSON> said that during his time awaiting trial in the <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jail </LOCATION>, he was stabbed six times by another inmate. In <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, those accused of first-degree murder are automatically jailed without bond pending trial. Prosecutor <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Cornely </PERSON> defended his case despite the identification problems. He said lengthy appeals over pre-trial motions hampered his efforts. `` We had other information, a confidential informant and certain other witnesses who knew something,'' said <PERSON> Cornely </PERSON>. `` But by the time the appeal was done, a lot had dried up.'' None of the five robbery victims at the bar could be located, he said. He shrugged off the the discrepancy over <PERSON> Alberja </PERSON>'s race. At the time of the robbery, bar owners <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Liles </PERSON> helped sketch a picture of the suspect, who they said was white. But after the tip from the informant almost four years later, investigators called in <LOCATION> Liles </LOCATION>, and he identified <PERSON> Alberja </PERSON> from a photo lineup. `` I do n't know what <PERSON> Liles </PERSON>' thinking was at first,'' said <PERSON> Cornely </PERSON>. `` Maybe the lighting in the bar made him think the suspect was white, but that's just a maybe.'' But <PERSON> Cornely </PERSON> acknowledged that <PERSON> Liles </PERSON>' change of testimony _ and a judge's decision to throw out the photo identification _ made his case impossible. `` His ID alone would not fly,'' said the prosecutor. `` We need other witnesses, and those witnesses disappeared.''
