<HEAD>World's Tallest Offshore Drilling Platform Travels Out To The Gulf</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CCI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INGLESIDE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Watching `` Bullwinkle'' head into the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> on Friday brought tears to the eyes of some who worked on the colossal offshore drilling platform that will be taller than <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s landmark Sears Tower. `` We've worked hard for three years, and an event like this can be somewhat emotional,'' said <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Offshore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s project manager for Bullwinkle. `` There were a few tears watching it go by.'' After the 1,368-foot, 50,000-ton Bullwinkle settles on the ocean floor off the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> coast, workers will install a deck and two drilling rigs, bringing the leviathan's weight to 78,000 tons and its height to 1,615 feet. `` That compares to the world's tallest building, which is the <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION>, which is about 1,450 feet,'' <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON> said. The tallest drilling platform is the 1,132-foot <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cognac </ORGANIZATION> platform, installed off the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> coast in 1976. Spectators lined the ship channel at <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aransas </LOCATION> on Friday to see the Bullwinkle off, and police had to direct traffic. Even lying on its side, it had no trouble dwarfing everything in sight. `` I made a trip up from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Padre </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> to watch Bullwinkle go out,'' <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> McSpadden </PERSON> said. `` I used to live in this town and I've followed its progress since its inception.'' Sterling has been in charge of the Bullwinkle project during three years of construction at the <LOCATION> Ingleside </LOCATION> yard of Gulf Marine Fabricators, which <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> contracted for construction, transportation and installation. `` We wish we were building another one right now, wish we had another one to start just as big as it or bigger,'' <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> vice president <PERSON> Myron </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodrigue </PERSON> said after watching nine tugboats pull the barge carrying the huge steel drilling jacket through the <ORGANIZATION> Corpus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ship </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Channel </ORGANIZATION>. At the project's peak, 700 people were employed in building the structure at <LOCATION> Ingleside </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Rodrigue </PERSON> said. Shell estimates the total cost of the Bullwinkle project at $ 500 million, including construction, installation and related expenses. The company would not specify how much the structure itself cost. The Bullwinkle, with a base measuring 4 -LCB- acres, has been a fixture on the horizon during its development, visible for several miles on the flat coastal plain in the <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION> area. Traffic on the Gulf Intracoastal Waterway was diverted at the beginning of May to prepare for loading the platform onto a specially built barge that measures 853 feet long, 207 feet wide and 49 feet deep. It is expected to take about three days to pull the structure 380 miles to its destination about 150 miles southwest of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. The base will be flooded to bring the drilling jacket to rest in 1,353 feet of water in <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canyon </LOCATION> lease, with installation expected to take about three months. Twenty-eight pilings for Bullwinkle will be driven 400 feet into the sea floor and secured with cement. Bullwinkle is designed to withstand at least a 72-foot hurricane wave, with the ability to sway more than 6 feet without stress damage. <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> estimates that production will begin in the first quarter of 1989, and will eventually put out 50,000 barrels of oil and 90 million cubic feet of natural gas per day. The Bullwinkle project was conceived nearly five years ago, when oil was well above $ 20 a barrel, <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON> said. `` Even today at $ 15 it's a -LRB- profitable -RRB- venture,'' he said, but added he will not brag until Bullwinkle is in place and producing. `` Bullwinkle'' was a code name given to the project when <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> was bidding for the Green Canyon underwater site.
