<HEAD>2,000 Protest Danube Power Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 2,000 Hungarian environmentalists marched to the Austrian Embassy on Friday to protest a <LOCATION> Danube </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> power project near <LOCATION> Nagymaros </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, which is being financed by <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, a participant said. The man said police refrained from interfering and even cleared the way for marchers through car-congested streets from downtown <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> to the embassy in the foreign diplomats' central district. The marcher, who spoke on condition of anonymity, called it an unusual sign of police cooperation with the young members of the unofficial <ORGANIZATION> Danube </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circle </ORGANIZATION> ecological group. In another departure, state-run television ran, without comment, a one-minute film segment on its main evening newscast showing protesters arriving at the embassy. Among them was biologist <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Varga </PERSON>, a leader of the ecologists. The marchers carried placards and banners demanding a halt to the project, a joint venture involving hydropower installations on the <LOCATION> Danube </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Gabcikovo </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and at Nagymaros. Banners read `` We Want Clear Water,'' `` No Dams'' and `` We Want Our Danube.'' Hungarian and Austrian ecologists have said that damming up the <LOCATION> Danube </LOCATION> water and slowing its flow will threaten drinking water reserves of millions of Hungarians and destroy large areas of riverside forestland in both <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Czechsolovakia </LOCATION>. The protester said demonstrators were met with applause and cheers from passers-by on the march to the embassy. Under an Austrian-Hungarian contract signed on May 29, 1986, 70 percent of the construction work $ 483 million will be carried out by Austrian companies. A delegation of four was allowed to enter the embassy to hand over a resolution protesting <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s financial participation, <ORGANIZATION> Austria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. It said the Austrian ambassador was not there but promised the protesters by telephone a written reply to their plea. The first turbine of the Nagymaros station is to go into operation in 1990. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> will repay construction costs by supplying <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> with electricity for 20 years, starting in 1996.
