<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-BusinessTaxes     05-27 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Business Taxes,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economists Criticize Business Tax System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A pair of top Soviet economists on Friday said progressive taxes on small businesses are an example of bureaucratic meddling that will discourage growth of consumer goods and services. <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aganbegyan </PERSON>, an economist close to Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, told reporters the progressive taxes as high as 90 percent were `` adopted behind closed doors'' by the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. `` Some provisions are faulty. They did n't know much about progressive taxation,'' he said. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has said the cooperatives _ employee-owned small businesses _ are a key element of his plans to improve the supply of goods and services to consumers, who face widespread shortages in the state-run economy. The Supreme Soviet, the country's nominal parliament, on Thursday passed a law expanding the rights of the cooperatives to compete with the inefficient state-run economy. And in a rare move, the body also expanded the rights of local government to give tax breaks to preferred kinds of cooperatives and directed that the progressive tax structure decreed April 1 by the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> be rewritten. The Supreme Soviet normally only rubber stamps legislation that already has been approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the dominant force in Soviet society. <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Shmelev </PERSON>, an economist with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A.-Canada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said the tax rates decreed by the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> apparently will remain in effect until they can be rewritten Tax rates for workers at cooperatives are 27 percent on a monthly income of $ 1,600 and 53.5 percent on an income of $ 3,200. The government has not said what income would be affected by the maximum 90 percent tax. The average industrial worker earns about $ 320 a month. Workers in the state sector pay a flat 13 percent tax if they earn more than $ 480 a month. `` I think this law on progressive taxation on cooperatives is very bad. It puts obstacles in the way of development of cooperatives,'' <PERSON> Shmelev </PERSON> said. He said the debate in the Supreme Soviet was an encouraging sign of life in that body. <PERSON> Aganbegyan </PERSON> said the tax rates probably would be on the books for a year or more before they could be amended. Eventually, he said a uniform progressive tax rate should be developed for those who work in cooperatives and those who for state-run enterprises. The law approved Thursday by the Supreme Soviet legally puts cooperatives on an equal footing with state-run enterprises. It ensures that cooperative property may not be seized by the state, allows cooperatives to own buildings and other property not including land, and them to conduct business with overseas companies and earn hard currency.
