<HEAD>Explosion in Garbage Truck Injures One</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An explosion in a garbage truck Friday night injured the driver and set the vehicle afire, police reported. Police spokesman <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Louw </PERSON> said the explosion occurred while a worker was loading a garbage bin into the back of the truck in downtown <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. He said the worker was not hurt but the driver suffered minor injuries to his face and one arm. <PERSON> Louw </PERSON> said police had not determined the cause but suspected it was a limpet mine, an explosive device that clings to other objects. There was no claim of responsibility. Police blame nearly all explosions the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the main guerrilla group fighting white domination. The <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Lusaka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>, seldom confirms or denies involvement in specific attacks but acknowledges using bombs in its campaign against the government. More than 70 bombings have been reported in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> since a nationwide state of emergency was declared June 12, 1986, to thwart an uprising in black townships. Two bombs went off Thursday in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, wounding four white women. The explosions coincided with the 40th anniversary of rule by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, architect of the apartheid policy that preserves power for the 5 million whites and denies a voice in national affairs to the 26 million blacks.
