<FIRST>r a AM-AIDS-BloodBank     05-27 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Blood Bank,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Closing Arguments Presented In AIDS Patient's Suit Against Blood
Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATTY REINERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The attorney for a woman who contracted AIDS through a 1983 blood transfusion told a jury Friday that the blood bank failed to screen donors properly and the doctors who saw her later treated her like `` a medical yo-yo.'' <PERSON> Susie </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON>, 50, of <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON>, and her husband, <PERSON> Chris </PERSON>, 53, are suing <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, whose blood bank in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, supplied the contaminated plasma; their former family doctor, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Merritt </PERSON>; and Dr. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Kearns </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> infectious disease expert who first tested Mrs. <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON> for exposure to the virus that causes AIDS. Lawyers have said the case may be the first case in the nation in which a jury will decide an AIDS victim's claim against a blood bank. In a 1986 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> case, a jury was chosen but the lawsuit was settled out of court before the trial ended. After closing arguments wind up, District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Coughlin </PERSON> said, he would allow the six-member jury to decide whether to recess for the holiday weekend or begin deliberations Saturday. The trial began three weeks ago. Mrs. <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Maureen </PERSON> <PERSON> Reidy </PERSON> <PERSON> Witt </PERSON>, said <ORGANIZATION> UBS </ORGANIZATION> and the doctors were uninformed and insensitive to the physical and emotional needs of their patient. <ORGANIZATION> UBS </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Irish </PERSON> said the jury must judge the defendants on the acceptable standards of care at the time <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON> received the transfusion, arguing that a test to detect AIDS virus in donated blood did not exist in 1983. He cautioned the jury that <ORGANIZATION> UBS </ORGANIZATION>' actions `` can not be judged by you using wisdom gained from hindsight.'' Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is a disease that attacks the body's immune system. It is transmitted through sexual contact or contact with an infected person's blood or bodily fluids. Mrs. <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON> received the deadly virus in a 1983 blood transfusion at <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cortez </LOCATION> during treatment for an accidental self-inflicted gunshot wound. The other two defendants, the two doctors, were accused of failing to properly diagnose or counsel her later. `` <PERSON> Susie </PERSON> was lonely, abandoned and scared and was a medical yo-yo betwen Dr. <PERSON> Merritt </PERSON> and Dr. <PERSON> Kearns </PERSON>, who said, ` You do have it, you do n't have it, you do have it,''' <PERSON> Witt </PERSON> said. `` That was in the spring of 1986, when they knew she had two positive test results.'' <PERSON> Witt </PERSON> said the doctors were also negligent in failing to explain to the couple what precautions they should have taken to prevent transmission of the disease. Although the couple testified they had sexual relations following the tests, <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON> has tested negative for the AIDS virus. Though <ORGANIZATION> UBS </ORGANIZATION> argued that the AIDS blood test became available only in 1985, <PERSON> Witt </PERSON> said the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> said in December 1982 that AIDS transmission was linked to homosexual and bisexual men and to blood transfusions. The blood bank had options to screen donors, such as direct questioning or physical examinations, <PERSON> Witt </PERSON> argued. `` United Blood Services chose d -RRB-, none of the above,'' he said. The lawsuit did n't specify the amount of damages sought, but <PERSON> Witt </PERSON> suggested the jury award damages of mroe than $ 13 million. Irish said in closing arguments that the defendants were sympathetic, and regret that she contracted AIDS from the transfusion. `` But the plaintiffs are not asking for our sympathy,'' Irish said. `` They are here to ask you to move a bag of money _ maybe $ 13 million, maybe more _ from this table to that table.'' Irish said the only person who can be blamed is the donor, who has admitted to carrying the AIDS virus. `` We are not liable for that man's conduct,'' Irish said.
