<FIRST>u a AM-FirefighterDeaths     05-27 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Firefighter Deaths,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firefighter Fatalities Up; Heart Attack Still Number One Killer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUINCY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of firefighters who died in the line of duty hit a seven-year high last year, with heart attacks again claiming the most lives, a national safety organization reported Friday. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> reported 124 fatalities in 1987, a 9.7 percent increase over the previous year and the most since 1981, when 134 firefighters died. There were 72 volunteers and 52 career firefighters among the 1987 fatalities, according to the non-profit group that claims more than 44,000 members nationwide. Overall, heart attacks continued to be the number one killer, striking down 56 firefighters, the group said. Other major causes of fatalities included internal trauma, 28 deaths; asphyxiation, 13 deaths; and crushing, 12 deaths. Of the heart attack victims, 14 had prior heart problems; 10 had severe heart disease; two suffered from hypertension and one was fatigued prior to the attack. Heart attack has been the major cause of firefighter fatalities since the study began 11 years ago, the group said. While the number of fatal heart attacks among firefighters over 40 years old was down 16 percent from the previous year, the numbers were slightly higher among younger firefighters. There were five fatal heart attack victims under 35 years old, including two under 20. Fifty-three firefighters were killed while fighting fires, with 24 dying from heart attacks, 10 from internal trauma, eight from smoke inhalation, six from being crushed, two from burns, two from gunshot wounds and one from electrocution. Thirty-five firefighters were killed while responding to or returning from an alarm. For the first time since the association began issuing the report, the largest proportion of deaths in the line of duty occurred during wildland fires. Seventeen firefighters were killed battling such blazes, while five died responding to or returning from wildland fires. Fires of suspicious origins accounted for 23 deaths, according to the statistics.
</TEXT>
