<HEAD>Coffee and Meat in Short Supply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Beef and pork have disappeared from meat counters throughout communist <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> as a new wave of shortages hit the country, a federal market inspectors' report to the government said Friday. Coffee was reported in sparse supply in some parts and cleaning powder can only be bought on and off, the <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Politika </ORGANIZATION> quoted as saying in their report. Other staples in short supply included butter, car tires, cement and some construction materials. Most Yugoslavs have been reported on a mass shopping spree in recent weeks in anticipation of steep price rises expected when a government price freeze ends next month. The new austerity program, aimed at curbing <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s highest inflation and repaying a $ 20 billion foreign debt, provides for further wage cuts and widespread price increases. The measures were originally due to start May 15 but were put off until June because new loans from Western creditors failed to materialize. The economic package is intended to reduce wages of Yugoslavs by up to 30 percent at a time when 80 percent of manufacturers announced new, higher prices for their products after the price freeze expires. Slovenian furniture manufacturers have already announced price increases of up to 80 percent and those of electric ware and paper products of up to 100 percent after the 6 -LCB- - month freeze is lifted To cope with the meat shortage, the government announced it was making available 20,000 tons of meat from emergency reserves. <PERSON> Bozidar </PERSON> <PERSON> Komadinic </PERSON>, director general of Centroproizvod company, said there was little hope that coffee will be available in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> any time soon, <ORGANIZATION> Politika </ORGANIZATION> reported.
</TEXT>
