<HEAD>British Business Programs Become Popular</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Talking about money is something that just was n't done in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> until only a few years ago Now, because of Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s capitalist revolution, business, economics and personal finance are increasingly popular subjects on British television. The number of television hours devoted to money matters has grown to more than 200 a year from about 30 hours annually just four years ago. `` Business is suddenly a much more interesting topic,'' said <PERSON> Caroline </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON>, independent Channel 4's commissioning editor for business, industry and science. The new shows have included a daily news show, a game show and even a dramatic series. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s two publicly funded <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> channels and two independent channels are all thinking money, but the biggest push has been made by Channel 4. In September it introduced `` Business Daily,'' a half-hour news program airing at midday Monday through Friday and targeted at professionals in the <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s financial district. In addition, Channel 4 introduced in January a Sunday night game show, `` The Stocks and Shares Show,'' in which contestants compete to make the most profit by investing play money in stocks. Channel 4 also recently ran a live weekly series called `` The Business Exchange,'' which gave advice to some of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s budding entrepreneurs on how to get financing and other topics. Also unusual was a six-part weekly dramatic series set in the City, rather than more typically in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s swanky neighborhoods, the cockney East End or the government's labyrinthian buildings. Called `` Killing on the Exchange,'' it ran on <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>'s main channel in prime time last year. `` There has been a big change in attitude in the past five years toward business with privatization and the Big Bang explosion in the City,'' Ms. <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> said. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> has privatized, or sold off, billions of pounds' worth of nationalized industries since she came into power in 1979, partly to get more shares into the hands of the British public The number of individual shareholders in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has trebled to 7 million in the nine years. Big Bang, most of which took place in October 1986, was a huge deregulation and computerization of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s financial services industry. `` Now, in Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, people can talk about profit without it being a dirty word,'' Ms. <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> said. Not all television viewers have been capitivated by these money matters programs. Ms. <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> conceded that talking about personal finances is still taboo for many Britons. `` The respectable thing in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is not to talk about finances, even how much they paid for a house. There are all sorts of traditions about not revealing how much you earn.'' she said. `` That's part of the British being rather buttoned-up people.'' The husband of a woman interviewed for `` Moneyspinner,'' a Channel 4 personal finances program, had a fit when he found out about it and insisted that the interview be deleted, Ms. <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> said. Still, `` Moneyspinner,'' which appears Tuesday nights in series of eight programs, is the most popular of the money shows on Channel 4, attracting about 2 million viewers. `` The Stocks and Shares Show'' has its detractors, too. `` It's caused more controversy than anything else I've done,'' Ms. <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> said. Critics feel the channel should n't encourage speculation, she said. The innovative programming comes on top of an increase in the number of more traditional types of money matters shows, such as the weekly current affairs programs and the odd documentary on, for example, insider trading. The oldest and most popular money program on British television is <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> 2's 22-year-old `` The Money Programme,'' a current-affairs show viewed by almost 3 million people on Sunday evenings. The show features hosts conducting studio interviews with business-world celebrities and expanded segments on newsworthy topics. The trend is evident in the theater, too. Currently running are the British plays `` Serious Money,'' which is also playing in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, and `` Speculators.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Elsewhere in television: FILMING STARTS _ `` Murderers Among Us: The <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiesenthal </PERSON> <PERSON> Story </PERSON>,'' a movie for <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION>, has gone into production in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, with Academy Award-winner <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Kingsley </PERSON> -LRB- `` Gandhi'' -RRB- playing the famous Nazi hunter. The movie also stars <PERSON> Renee </PERSON> <PERSON> Soutendijk </PERSON> as <PERSON> Wiesenthal </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Cyla </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> as an American military officer who helped <PERSON> Wiesenthal </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
