<HEAD>African National Congress Attracts Some South African Whites</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite repeated setbacks, the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> presses on with military and underground efforts to unseat the apartheid government. Some of its new guerrilla recruits are young whites. `` There is a continuing trend of young, well-educated liberal and left-wing whites to identify themselves with the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Lodge </PERSON>, a political scientist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witwatersrand </ORGANIZATION> and an expert on the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>. Increasingly, he added, the whites see the organization as `` a legitimate and morally admirable political force.'' Police say they have seized <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> whites with caches of arms, arrested another in a car bombing and charged at least one with treason. But <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> military activities have diminished. In the past year, bombings in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> have declined, police have claimed major breakthroughs against <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas, and even the organization's leaders have conceded that its military actions were more effective during the widespread unrest of 1984-86. <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas generally operate in small groups and have little hope of scoring conventional victories against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s powerful security forces However, the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> says its bombing and sabotage campaign remains an essential element of its multi-pronged strategy to oust the white-led government. `` We must step up our attacks on the police, the army and other personnel associated with the institution -LRB- government -RRB-,'' <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Tambo </PERSON> said in March in neighboring, black-governed <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>. `` We will strike against its economic infrastructure and do much more intensively what we have been doing all the time.'' However, the talk has not been matched by action. Two years ago, the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> was claiming that it had enough popular support in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to direct a `` people's power'' campaign that would make the country ungovernable. But since the government imposed a nationwide state of emergency in June 1986, black unrest has dwindled from daily outbursts across the country to sporadic, isolated incidents. <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> activity has declined simultaneously. Fifty bombings were reported in the first year of the emergency but only about 20 in the past 11 months. Police say that since the beginning of 1987 they have killed 54 suspected <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> members and captured 525, inflicting major setbacks to <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> operations inside <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` Terrorists who are sent to the republic -LRB- <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> -RRB- are going on suicide missions, because confrontation with the security forces means either certain death or a long period of imprisonment,'' said <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>, the government's law and order minister. However, the recent defeats do not appear to have hampered the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>'s ability to recruit members into its military wing, known as Umkhonto we Sizwe -LRB- Spear of the Nation -RRB-. `` People do n't join the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> if they are worried about setbacks,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sebina </PERSON>, a spokesman at <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Lusaka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>. `` People have joined _ and they continue to join _ because they are committed to our liberation struggle.'' The <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> refuses to say what its membership is, but it is variously estimated at 4,000 to 10,000 men with military training, most of whom are in camps in <LOCATION> Tanzania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. No more than a few hundred are believed to be inside <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Whites always have had some role in <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> political activities, some of them in its upper echelons, but spokesman <PERSON> Sebina </PERSON> said the involvement of young whites has been growing in the 1980s, though he declined to give any figures. When police arrested four whites May 8 at a farmhouse outside <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, they claimed their largest arms seizure ever. The whites had a Soviet-made SAM-7 ground-to-air missile, limpet mines, hand grenades, machine guns, mortars and explosives, the police said. The leading suspect in a car bombing that killed three people March 17 is a 24-year-old white man whose father is a university journalism professor. In <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Schreiner </PERSON>, a 31-year-old white whose father is a university administrator, is on trial with 12 black co-defendants charged with treason and terrorism. The government portrays the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> as a communist-led terrorist group that kills civilians and lacks widespread support and political legitimacy. `` The conviction that the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> is conducting a futile struggle is already taking root in the their ranks,'' said <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>, the law and order minister. The government also claims the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> is torn by internal strife, that numerous of its defectors have joined the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> police force and that the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> keeps its dissidents in at an `` inhuman'' detention camp in northern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sebina </PERSON> denied those claims. He said South African agents, not internal <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> feuding, were behind the six killings this year of <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> officials living outside <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. He disclaimed any knowledge of recent defections by ranking <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> members and said the organization did not maintain detention camps for dissidents. `` The government has been making similar noises for a long time,'' said <PERSON> Sebina </PERSON>. `` They said our back was broken when we were outlawed -LRB- in 1960 -RRB-. They said the same thing when -LRB- <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> was arrested -LRB- in 1962 -RRB-. One or two defeats will not end our struggle.'' <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> leader at the time of his arrest, is in prison but remains a rallying point for the organization and the large majority of blacks. Founded in 1912 as a black rights movement, the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> took up arms in 1961, the year after it was banned, saying it was left with no alternative. It is the largest black group fighting the government, and it is widely believed that the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> would win national elections if the country's 26 million blacks were allowed to vote. The <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> has offices in many African nations as well as <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in hopes of advancing its political fortunes. The <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> has been drawing up a new set of guidelines for a post-apartheid constitution that is reported to be their most detailed political document ever. The Weekly Mail newspaper of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> said the proposal calls for a mixed economy, a bill of rights and a multi-party government. It also calls for equalizing wealth, a sensitive issue in a country where blacks make up about 75 percent of the population but own less than 2 percent of the country's fixed assets. The most contentious issue involving the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> remains its use of violence. The government says it wo n't talk to the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> until it lays down its arms. The <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> says the arms are necessary to bring the government into genuine negotiations. `` There has been no reassessment of the armed struggle,'' said <PERSON> Sebina </PERSON>. `` There are still bombs exploding here and there, and I'm sure there will be more of them.
</TEXT>
