<NOTE>For Release Sun June 5 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LIFE ABROAD: Yugoslavia _ Shattered Dreams on the Farm</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 This is one of a series of periodic reports by <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> correspondents on life and times in other countries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SKOBALJ, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Radisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrovic </PERSON>, a farmer's son, left this sleepy village for college 10 years ago with dreams of `` a normal life'' _ having a car and an apartment in the city. What he did n't know then, however, was that his country's economy would falter under the weight of heavy borrowing, bad investment and a mounting debt Today he is back on the farm, one of millions of young Yugoslavs forced to depend on their parents for economic survival. <PERSON> Petrovic </PERSON>, 30, who married a law student at the university in nearby <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, now is driving his father's old Soviet-made car. His wife, <PERSON> Tanja </PERSON>, has joined more than 1 million Yugoslavs who are out of work, staying at home with an 18-month-old daughter instead of defending court cases. As an agrarian manager on a state-run pig farm, <PERSON> Petrovic </PERSON> earns an above-average 370,000 dinar -LRB- $ 250 -RRB- a month. It does n't go far in an inflation of 170 percent and an economy burdened by a $ 21 billion foreign debt the Communist government is strapped to pay. `` My monthly salary lasts three days,'' joked <PERSON> Petrovic </PERSON>. `` Twenty if I'm really economical. After that, <PERSON> Papa </PERSON> must come with his money.'' The Petrovics rarely eat out. The traditional vacation on the <LOCATION> Adriatic </LOCATION> will happen this year only if a relative lends them a seaside home and the couple finds the money to repair the Soviet car. On the surface, life in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> sometimes seems blissfully untouched by the economic woes. Bars and cafes in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, the capital, are always full. The young dress with style. Cars and Western gadgets are conspicuous. Behind that facade, however, living standards have dropped one-third since 1980 when Yugoslavs thought they had something to look ahead to. The inflation that Premier <PERSON> Branko </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON> has called a destructive evil is eating away at the fragile infrastructure of a nation constantly troubled by ethnic tensions among peoples divided in six different republics and using two different alphabets, Roman and cyrillic. Many of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s 23 million citizens depend for survival on the only structures left intact _ the traditional bonds between family and friends, and age-old ties to the land. `` People who live with their parents live much better than those who do n't,'' <PERSON> Petrovic </PERSON> told a visitor. `` Being dependent on your parents, you have a chance to sit in a car, live a bit normally. If you separate ... forget a car, forget a TV, forget everything.'' The 300 families of Skobalj are relatively well off on the fertile land along the <LOCATION> Danube </LOCATION> southeast of <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>. But even they say times are getting hard, and they angrily criticize the Communist hierarchy's policy of curbing farming output. `` This is the worst situation I can remember,'' said <PERSON> Borivoje </PERSON> <PERSON> Stojadinovic </PERSON>, 65, who has farmed here all his life. Sitting out on his porch, sipping coffee with visitors, <PERSON> Stojadinovic </PERSON> recalled selling a bull in 1938 for 4,000 dinars. `` You could have bought half the village,'' he said. Now, 4,000 dinars is barely worth $ 3. A decade ago, <PERSON> Stojadinovic </PERSON> added, the sale of a bull provided his home with a refrigerator and washing machine. Now, he added, `` I'd need two bulls _ one for each.'' He and his wife <PERSON> Radmila </PERSON>, 62, sold two of their 17 acres of land years back to finance the education of their two daughters, one now a doctor and the other an engineer in different Serbian cities. Both are married. But both still depend on their increasingly frail parents to survive. `` I ca n't send money,'' the father said. `` But just the other day I sent one of them a nice, fat pig.'' The Stojadinovics would like to lease out land they ca n't farm for extra cash. Down the lane, <PERSON> Dusan </PERSON> <PERSON> Pantic </PERSON> would like to rent it to graze his prize-winning cows and expand the farm he runs with his wife and son. But the rent Pantic would be able to pay would n't cover taxes and other state levies, <PERSON> Stojadinovic </PERSON> said. Communist authorities curb expansion for successful farmers like <PERSON> Pantic </PERSON>, forbidding any peasant to farm more than 25 acres of land. Former university student <PERSON> Petrovic </PERSON>, sitting at the kitchen table of his father's farmhouse, railed against such rules. `` They should take a look at what the Western world did with agriculture,'' he said. A prize cow in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, he added, yields less than one quarter of the milk of an average cow in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Ninety percent of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s agriculture is in the hands of private farmers like <PERSON> Petrovic </PERSON>'s father. `` But there are no good, stimulating measures for private producers here,'' <PERSON> Petrovic </PERSON> said, advocating new measures to create bigger, more efficient farms. Like many other reforms in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, planned improvements in farming have run awry. <PERSON> Petrovic </PERSON> cited a plan to give loans to farmers whose investments yield slow returns and who must sell produce to the state at prices that lag behind inflation. `` The wrong people got the credits,'' <PERSON> Petrovic </PERSON> said. `` They have nothing to do with agriculture and just use the money to build houses and buy cars.'' Asked why, <PERSON> Petrovic </PERSON> flashed the knowing smile of someone accustomed to a nation where connections and power open doors. `` We have some strange laws,'' he said. `` The law here is not a law if there are no exceptions.'' A few miles up river in the village of <LOCATION> Grocka </LOCATION>, the wealth of local officials is on show. Mercedes cars sit in the driveways of their weekend homes and in the parking lot of a local restaurant favored by the late President <PERSON> Josip </PERSON> <PERSON> Broz </PERSON> <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>. The only other people not suffering around Skobalj are those who went off to work in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, like a million other Yugoslavs, and have returned to build brick houses. `` Most of the people who went abroad in earlier years were poor and uneducated,'' <PERSON> Petrovic </PERSON> said. `` They went because of the hard economic situation for them. Now, they are coming back richer and cleverer than all the people left here.'' He said a schoolfriend went to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> years ago to play handball. `` Now, he drives a Porsche.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sun June 5</NOTE>
