<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy grew at a surprisingly rapid annual rate of 3.9 percent from January through March, much better than previously believed, the government said. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday that the gross national product, the broadest measure of economic health, was propelled during the first three months of the year by an export surge, a rebound in car sales and a boom in business capital investment. The report represented a sharp upward revision from an initial estimate made a month ago that the GNP grew at a more modest 2.3 percent rate in the first quarter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
