<SECOND>PM-Auto Quality,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Porsche Comes in First in Car Quality Survey; Three GM Makes Reach
Top 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Porsche placed first in an annual survey naming the 10 most trouble-free cars, while three <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> models made the list, two of them for the first time. The J.D. <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> car quality survey was mailed to 75,000 owners of new 1988 model cars purchased in November and December and asked for the number of problems experienced during the first 90 days. The survey results were announced Thursday. More than 30,000 owners answered the 1988 survey, said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, senior project director for the <LOCATION> Agoura </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, consulting firm. The results: Porsche topped the list of most trouble-free cars with 111 problems reported per 100 cars. Porsche cars came in sixth in 1987. Bumped to the second spot by <ORGANIZATION> Porsche </ORGANIZATION> was <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION>, a fellow West German automaker whose owners reported 115 problems per 100 cars in 1988, up from 108 in 1987, when it placed first. <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> tied for third place with 122 problems per 100 cars, an improvement for both. In 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> was third with 125 problems and <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> was fourth with 129. <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>'s upscale Acura line slipped to fifth in 1988 from second in 1987. Owners reported 138 problems per 100 cars in 1988, up from 117 in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Daihatsu </ORGANIZATION>, which ranked as the sixth most trouble-free car, barely made it into the 1988 survey, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said, because the company began selling cars in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in December. <ORGANIZATION> Daihatsu </ORGANIZATION> owners reported 141 problems per 100 cars. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s Cadillac, with 143 problems per 100 cars was seventh, while <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION>, with 153, was eighth and Oldsmobile, with 157, placed ninth. <PERSON> Cadillac </PERSON> and <PERSON> Oldsmobile </PERSON> made the list for the first time since J.D. Powers began the survey in 1985. No American models made the list in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>'s other lines fell to No. 10, with 158 problems per 100 cars compared to the 130 problems that put the company in fifth place in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Subaru </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> BMW </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION>, which ranked seventh through 10th in 1987, did not make the list this year. <PERSON> J.D </PERSON>. Powers reports only the top 10 rankings, and in 1987, it announced the number of trouble reports for only the top five cars. `` We discovered there is a relationship between customer satisfaction and the problems that owners experience,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. He said results of the short-term car quality survey have been mirrored in the J.D. Power Customer Satisfaction Index, a rating of dealers produced by surveying owners 12 months after their purchase. The CSI is important to auto dealers because auto manufacturers use it to determine which dealers receive hot new models, new car lines or even new brands. Dealers have complained that the <ORGANIZATION> CSI </ORGANIZATION> reflects problems with vehicles more than problems with dealers, making dealers suffer for manufacturers mistakes. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said both dealer and vehicle quality play in the CSI ratings. `` The more problems, the more pressure on the dealer to fix the car,'' he said, adding that previous survey shows about 50 percent of the problems customers bring back to dealerships are repaired.
</TEXT>
