<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> remains `` a few more quarters'' of operating profitability away from restoring the dividend the beleaguered banking giant dropped in 1985, its chairman said. But A.W. <PERSON> Clausen </PERSON> painted an upbeat picture of prospects for the nation's third-largest bank holding company at <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION>'s annual shareholders meeting Thursday. `` <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> is on the road to recovery,'' <PERSON> Clausen </PERSON> said at a news conference preceding the meeting. `` Our turnaround was grounded on a realistic plan to focus on core objectives, to improve the performance of the credit portfolio, and to bring our expenses and revenues into profitable alignment,'' he said. As proof of the recovery, <PERSON> Clausen </PERSON> pointed to a 62 percent increase in first-quarter 1988 profit, decreases in net credit losses over the past six quarters, and reduced expenses from operations and the sale of nonstrategic businesses. <PERSON> Clausen </PERSON> also noted reductions in core business expenses, such as personnel, and increases in net interest income during 1987 and strengthening of the bank's primary capital ratio over the past six quarters. `` Our challenge is to improve fundamental net income on a quarter-by-quarter basis, to bring in each quarter's fundamental earnings at a higher level than the previous quarter, and to extend the recent track record of solid and continuous profitability,'' he said. <PERSON> Clausen </PERSON>, a former head of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> who returned as chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> in late 1986, drew a salary of $ 775,000 last year. <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> stock closed 12.5 cents higher at $ 10.375 a share in composite trading Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. In 1987, <ORGANIZATION> BankAmerica </ORGANIZATION> reported a net loss of $ 955 million, which followed a 1986 loss of $ 518 million. The company recorded a profit for the first time in six quarters in the third period of 1987, posting net income of $ 54 million. For the first quarter of 1988, the company reported net income of $ 109 million, or 56 cents a share, up from a profit of $ 67 million, or 34 cents a share, a year earlier. The company reported higher earnings for the third straight quarter.
