<FIRST>r f PM-CableJobs     05-27 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cable Jobs,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cable Study Says Industry A Rising Star</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The cable television industry will contribute about $ 32 billion to the gross national product during 1988 and provide some 490,000 jobs, a report commissioned by a cable-related company says. The study was done by <PERSON> Browne </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Bortz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Coddington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> research firm, after being commissioned by <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Daniels </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, a major cable TV financial services company based in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. The study updated a 1986 report prepared by the same company which also was sponsored by <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>. The cable industry in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has continued to grow rapidly over the past two years with annual revenue now around $ 12.8 billion, a 24.3 percent increase since 1986, the report said. The industry provides 87,600 direct jobs, and cable-related work provides an additional 60,000 jobs. Another 340,000 jobs are created indirectly, according to he report. Cable-related employment expanded at a lower rate than either economic output or employee income during that time, and the report concluded that `` economic output per employee increased over the past two years, resulting in fewer employees per dollar of economic output.'' The study said cable came of age during the late 1980s with half of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> households now subscribing to cable service; 75 percent of the subscribers now have access to 30 or more program channels; 15 percent have access to 54 or more. Cable-originated programming makes up almost 40 percent of viewing in the average cable home, the report said, while viewing of network-affiliated broadcast stations dropped 12 percent in the past five years. `` Our country is in the midst of a communications revolution,'' <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said. `` During this decade, all media and communications industries grew rapidly, but cable television has been the star performer.'' The study said that in revenue terms, cable television ranks ahead of motion picture box office, radio, home video and broadcast network advertising.
