 The dollar ended the week marginally higher against the Japanese yen in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> today, while stock prices dipped for the second consecutive trading day. The dollar closed at 124.64 yen, up 0.14 yen from its finish on Thursday. It opened at 124.61 yen and moved between 124.58-125 .66 yen during the day `` Participants stayed away from making major moves in anticipation that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> might raise its official interest rates to cool the economy, following the announcement of a higher growth rate for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product,'' said an official of a major commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity. It was reported Thursday that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product had grown by 3.9 percent in the first three months of the year, up from 2.3 percent originally reported. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, which slipped a modest 15.41 points Thursday, lost another 137.75 points, or 0.5 percent, to finish the day's trading at 27,290.49. `` Share prices went down sharply just before the end of the afternoon session led by profit-taking in pharmaceutical issues,'' said <PERSON> Masahiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Umemori </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest brokerage. The fear of rising inflation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was strong among investors, he added. Volume on the first section was estimated at 1.3 billion shares, up from the 1.1 billion shares traded Thursday. Traders attributed the high volume figure to active trading in large capital issues, such as heavy industrials and steels.
