<SECOND>PM-US-Canada Trade,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Finds U.S.-Canada Trade Pact Would Hurt Some U.S. Industries</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A proposed treaty that would remove most tariff barriers between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> probably would increase trade between the two countries but leave some <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industries at a competitive disadvantage, a private study says. The study by the <ORGANIZATION> Northeast-Midwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a research group established by members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, found that `` the impact of the proposed agreement likely would be uneven, with some industries gaining and others losing.'' The report, released Thursday, said that the automotive and textile industries would be the big losers under the treaty, now being considered by committees in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. In both the automobile and textile industries, Canadian tariffs would be retained during a phase-out period stretching up to 10 years, making it harder for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industries to compete, the study said. The treaty also would allow <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> to establish new barriers in the textile sector, the study noted. On the other hand, the study said, industrial machinery, electronics and energy-intensive industries in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would benefit from the agreement, in part because of already low Canadian tariffs or more rapid removal of duties under the treaty. `` The stakes are high for Northeastern and <LOCATION> Midwestern </LOCATION> states, where about 72 percent of total trade between the two countries occurs,'' the study said. About half the 2 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> jobs that are dependent upon exports to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> are located within 12 states, nine of them in the <LOCATION> Northeast-Midwest </LOCATION> region, the study said. In 1986, Canadian exports to the region totaled $ 49 billion, which was about 72 percent of all Canadian shipments to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the study said. The region exported $ 33 billion in goods and services to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, representing about 73 percent of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shipments to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. The study found that <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> states would benefit from improved access to cheap Canadian hydroelectric power and a better chance to compete in the service sector. The <LOCATION> mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> states, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in particular, would benefit from lower prices for Canadian raw materials, but would be hurt by the continuation of Canadian restrictive technical standards for telecommunications equipment, the study said. The <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> in particular, would be hurt by continued barriers that give <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> a competitive edge in the automotive industry, the study said. However, lower raw material costs would increase the manufacturers' `` ability to be price competitive in world markets,'' the study said. The <ORGANIZATION> Northeast-Midwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> serves senators and representatives of 18 states: <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>.
