<FIRST>r f PM-FAA-Boeing     05-27 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FAA-Boeing,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Modifications Proposed For Older Boeing 737s</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government is proposing modifications to older <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s to help the aging aircraft stand up against the corrosion and crack problems discovered after the breakup of an <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet last month. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday issued two proposed `` airworthiness directives'' designed to serve as long-term solutions to the structural problems identified after a 20-foot section of the Aloha plane tore away during flight on April 28. While some ongoing intensified inspections would be required under the proposed rules, airlines could avoid even more intensive and costly inspections once they completed the modifications. `` We're giving the airlines what we call a ` terminating action,' something they can do so they do n't have to continue to do these very expensive, repetitive inspections,'' <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said of the proposed modifications. The rules cover, in varying degrees, the first 464 of the 737s built, but only an estimated 100 of those aircraft now are being operated by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines. The repairs were expected to take about 2,000 work hours per plane, with the total cost for work on the 100 planes operated by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers estimated at $ 8 million. `` This proposal is prompted by reports of numerous cracks found during inspections of airplanes that have accumulated more than 40,000 landings,'' one of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> proposals states. `` This condition, if not corrected, could result in rapid decompression of the airplane.'' The Aloha jetliner was 19 years old and had made nearly 89,000 landings. The proposed modifications would involve using rivets rather than bonding agents to attach metal tear strips that join pieces of the fuselage. They also would require the replacement of certain countersunk rivets with larger rivets that have protruding heads. The heads of countersunk rivets are set at or below the surface into which they are driven. The countersunk rivets are suspected of having caused small cracks in the skin of the plane that could grow and eventually join into one large crack, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> reported on Tuesday that a special inspection of 96 older <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s had revealed small cracks in one of every nine aircraft but not of a magnitude to cause alarm. The inspection is ongoing. <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said the new rules were `` aimed at stopping the cause of the cracks in the first place.'' `` We're fairly certain that most of the cracks that we're concerned with came from the fact that there were countersunk rivets,'' he said The proposed rules are subject to public comment until July 24.
</TEXT>
