<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At least 64 production companies signed independent contracts with the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> as union members, claiming they had split management ranks, gathered to decide whether to accept the agreements. Six more producer requests for contracts were turned in to union officials by Thursday night, when approximately 1,500 guild writers met at the <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paladium </LOCATION> to cast their votes. East Coast members of the guild cast ballots Thursday night in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The results of the voting were to be announced this afternoon, union spokeswoman <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> said here. The 9,000-member guild claimed the contracts effectively split management ranks among the makers of such hit productions as `` The Cosby Show'' and `` The Tonight Show.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION>, representing the industry's biggest producers, downplayed the defections, which represent the first significant break in the 12-week strike that has forced delays in the start of the fall TV season. `` We're anticipating ratification,'' Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> said before the meeting. `` We see it strategically as a good move at this time to break the logjam with the alliance.'' Meanwhile, negotiators for both the alliance and the guild agreed to meet in small groups Saturday and in aother full-dress bargaining session Tuesday. Among the terms in the three-year independent contracts are a 35 percent formula for foreign residuals and greater creative input, two of the major points of contention with the alliance since the March 7 walkout. The alliance is offering 10.3 percent for foreign residuals, said spokesman <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>. Residuals are the fees paid to writers when TV shows are rerun or movies reissued. The list of 64 production companies released at the meeting includes the <ORGANIZATION> Carsey-Werner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, which produces two of the most popular shows on television, `` The Cosby Show'' and its spinoff, `` A Different World.'' The makers of `` The Tonight Show'' signed a contract and the producers of `` Late Night with <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Letterman </PERSON>'' have agreed to a contract but have n't signed, said union President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirgo </PERSON>. Among the others to sign were producers of `` <PERSON> Alf </PERSON>,'' `` The Muppets'' and `` Highway to Heaven.'' <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said none of the 217 major producers that belong to the alliance has signed independent contracts. Large producers, whose ranks include <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> MTM </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON>, employ 80 percent of the industry's writers and supply 84 percent of prime-time TV shows, he said. `` The alliance producers are holding strong,'' <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said. `` Our objective is to get this town back to work and get everybody working.'' He estimated that the independent deals would only re-employ about 72 writers. `` If they're satisfied to put 72 writers to work and leave 4,000 out of work, that's their choice,'' he said. `` They have no way to estimate that number,'' Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> responded. `` They just pulled that out of thin air the way they do with all of their other figures.''
