<FIRST>u f PM-TelevisedRoots Bjt   05-27 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Televised Roots, Bjt,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Use Tiny Video Camera in Own `Roots' Production</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>URBANA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Agricultural researchers are doing their own production of `` Roots'' by inserting a tiny video camera into the soil to record the underground development of soybean plants. The technique could help scientists understand how various tillage systems affect crop growth, as well as when and where to apply fertilizer and pesticide. `` I think it will work and it will be an important tool,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Levan </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> researcher who worked on the project with <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> engineers <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hummel </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Sudduth </PERSON>. The 1 - by 3-inch video camera is guided down clear plastic tubes inserted in the bean rows and used to record root growth from a few inches to more than 3 feet below the surface `` It's not very spectacular as movies go, I'm afraid,'' said <PERSON> Hummel </PERSON>, scanning one tape. Depth markers can be read on the inside of the tube, and white soybean roots can be seen in the earth. Occasionally, an insect moves into the frame to nibble on a root. `` I saw a soybean beetle,'' said <PERSON> Levan </PERSON>. `` The root was very prominent _ new, large and white _ and there was the worm chewing through it. It was real clear.'' The tubes are inserted in the ground at an angle soon after planting so the soybean crop can be checked throughout the season. In two previous seasons, the focus has been on perfecting the technique. Without the video equipment, scientists must remove cores of soil, section them, wash off the dirt and measure roots, <PERSON> Levan </PERSON> said. That method does not allow observation of the same roots throughout the season, she said. <PERSON> Hummel </PERSON> said the tiny camera actually was designed to inspect the inside of pipes in nuclear power plants. In the UI study, some soybeans being monitored are planted in undisturbed soil while others are planted after deep, thorough plowing. `` It also should be helpful for fertilizer placement because it tells you where the active roots are during the growing season,'' said <PERSON> Levan </PERSON>. `` Also, you can observe insects that attack roots and see when they hatch and where they feed.'' That might help scientists determine the best time and location for insecticides, and it should help them compare the results of various products by watching them work in the soil, the researchers said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
