 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar held steady in thin European trading early today. Gold prices fell. Traders said market activity was dampened by the absence of many senior foreign exchange dealers attending a convention in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. As well, an approaching long weekend in the major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and British markets undermined dealers' willingness to take new positions. `` It's going to be a day of low business volume and few people to talk to,'' said a trader with a West German bank in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading stops before the start of the <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> business day, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency closed at 124.64 Japanese yen, up from 124.50 yen late Thursday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> trading later today, the dollar was quoted at 124.70 yen. Midmorning dollar rates, compared with late Thursday, included: 1.7090 West German marks, up from 1.7080; 1.4260 Swiss francs, up from 1.4257; 5.7620 French francs, unchanged; 1.9125 Dutch guilders, unchanged; 1,268.50 Italian lire, up from 1,268.00, and 1.2380 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2374 The dollar rose against the British pound, which was quoted at $ 1.8592, compared with $ 1.8625 on Thursday. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s major bullion dealers fixed a recommended gold price of $ 452.50 a troy ounce, down from $ 453.30 late Thursday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold was bid at $ 452.70, down from $ 454. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, closed at a bid of $ 454.12, up from $ 452.42. Silver bullion was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid of $ 6.58 a troy ounce, down from $ 6.63.
