<HEAD>Guilty Plea in Computer Conspiracy Case
^Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A computer whiz has pleaded guilty to conspiring to sell $ 4 million in stolen supercomputer technology to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> of Fremont admitted in federal court on Thursday he took part in a scheme with three other people to sell the Soviets plans to a system that allows computers to process as many as 1 billion instructions per second. The technology had a restricted rather than classified status but could have proved damaging to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> security if the Soviets had received it, according to the government. The deal was broken up by government agents who infiltrated the scheme, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Russoniello </PERSON> said when arrests were made last year. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> pleaded guilty to conspiring to violate export laws and wire fraud, based on his use of the telephone to defraud <ORGANIZATION> Saxpy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Sunnyvale </LOCATION>, from which the plans were stolen. In exchange, prosecutors dropped about a dozen other charges against the former software engineer at <ORGANIZATION> Synthesized </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clara </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> faces up to 15 years in prison and a fine of up to $ 20.3 million at sentencing July 15. The plea came two weeks before an extradition hearing in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> for <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> McVey </PERSON>, an alleged conspirator in the scheme. He is being held in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ivan-Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Batinic </PERSON>, an engineer who once worked fr Saxpy, and his brother <PERSON> Stevan </PERSON> also were charged in the case. According to court documents, <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> had planned to use an elaborate money-laundering scheme involving <LOCATION> Liechtenstein </LOCATION> banks to set up a computer business in <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, after completing the sale to the Soviets.
