<HEAD>April After-Tax Income Down, Consumption Spending Stagnant</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with five grafs to UPDATE with income and spending
report today. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, The growth ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Tax filings took a big chunk from Americans' disposable income last month and compelled them to cut spending substantially, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported today. It said after-tax incomes fell 0.9 percent in April, the sharpest setback in a year and the first decline since a 0.6 percent drop in November. Personal consumption spending was basically stagnant in April following a 0.8 percent rise in March, the department said. In April 1987, changes prompted by the new tax law took a bigger bite out of Americans' incomes and reduced their disposable income by 2.5 percent. Before adjusting for taxes, personal income rose a weak 0.1 percent in April following a 1.1 percent jump in March. This performance was substantially below the expectations of many economists, who have predicted strong economic growth this year. Evidence of that strong growth was reported Thursday by the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which said the gross national product grew at a surprisingly rapid annual rate of 3.9 percent in the first three months of the year. The growth was much better than anticipated and came largely from surging exports, higher auto sales and increased business capital investment. `` You would have to say that not only was the stock market crash ignored, but the economy thumbed its nose at it,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON>, chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The report reflected a sharp upward revision from an initial estimate made a month ago that the GNP grew at a more modest 2.3 percent rate in the first quarter. It elated Republicans, who are hoping a record 66-month-long expansion since the last recession of 1981-82 will bolster prospects that Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will win the White House in the November election. But to the stock and bond markets, sensitive barometers of the economy's future direction, the GNP report was widely viewed as another signal that higher inflation is inevitable. The inflation signal was substantiated by another government report Thursday showing after-tax corporate profits rose only 0.5 percent in the first quarter. Some economists suggested that meant companies will attempt to boost their profits by raising prices. On Wall Street, stocks gained only marginally Thursday in light trading, reflecting an apathy that has persisted for months. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.38 points to 1,966.75 after falling 1.16 the day before. Bond prices were mostly lower. The key 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond fell \ point or $ 2.50 for every $ 1,000 in face value, and its yield, which moves inversely to its price, climbed to 9.32 percent from 9.28 percent late Wednesday. Many analysts have predicted that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, responsible for restraining inflation, will push interest rates higher to dampen demand for credit. The central bank has tightened credit twice in the past two months. Some said the fast GNP growth was an advance signal of a 1989 recession, despite White House assertions that the number harbored no bad news.
