<HEAD>Texaco Directors Reject Icahn Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 2-3 to CLARIFY directors called contest costly,
battle launched this morning; uppicks 4th graf pvs: In rejecting
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s board today rejected a $ 60-a-share buyout offer from takeover artist <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> and denounced the bid as a pressure tactic. The directors also called on <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> to abandon what they described as his `` costly and disruptive'' proxy contest, in which he is seeking five seats on the oil giant's board. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> launched the proxy battle this morning before the board formally gathered to consider the offer, which values <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> at $ 14.6 billion. Spokesman <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Call </PERSON> said <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> did not want to waste time and decided to mail ballots for his slate of candidates before the long Memorial Day weekend began. In rejecting the offer, the <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> board cited a number of factors they claimed undermined the seriousness of the bid. They echoed management's sentiments in questioning whether <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> could arrange financing and said the 48-hour deadline he imposed on the offer indicated he was not serious. The board said it was confident <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s restructuring program would enhance shareholder value. Analysts were skeptical that <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s board would approve <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s offer. `` I would be flabbergasted if <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s board agreed to <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s merger proposal,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, who follows <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> for <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co He joined others in suggesting that the offer was doomed from the beginning and that <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s largest shareholder, was fully aware of that. Wall Street remained unenthusiastic. Shares in the nation's third largest oil company eased 50 cents to $ 49.50 a share in afternoon trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> battled it out in competing full-page ads in selected newspapers today _ with <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> asking shareholders if they can trust the company's future to <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, and the takeover strategist urging them to take up his offer. Analysts suggested <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s real intention in making the bid was to push <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s stock price up as he continued his war of nerves against the management of the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, N.Y.-based company. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s offer of $ 60 for each of <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s 243 million shares would value the company at $ 14.6 billion. However, under the offer, he would have to pay out only $ 12.4 billion for the 207 million shares he does not already own. He paid an average $ 34 a share, or about $ 1.22 billion, for his existing stake of 36 million shares. The combined total of $ 13.64 billion would amount to the biggest sum ever paid in a corporate buyout. The previous record was a $ 13.4 billion acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, now <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, in 1984. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnear </PERSON>, in a statement released Thursday, reiterated his claim that <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s offer was bogus. `` There is no basis to believe that Mr. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> can arrange the financing for a transaction of approximately $ 20 billion _ including the purchase of the shares he does n't own ... and the payment of debt and other obligations that would have to be satisified in connection with his proposal,'' <PERSON> Kinnear </PERSON> said. When making the offer on Wednesday, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> said he was so sure he could obtain financing that he would place $ 100 million in escrow and forfeit it to <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> if he failed to get commitments before the company's annual shareholders meeting next month _ subject to certain conditions. The struggle has been escalating since last fall when <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> began building what has become a 14.8 percent stake in <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>. Today, that stake is so large that he can not sell it quickly _ and collect his profit _ without depressing its price on the market. `` I think he wants somebody to bail him out,'' said <PERSON> Cliff </PERSON> <PERSON> Haigler </PERSON>, an analyst at the securities firm <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weil </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labouisse </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Friedrichs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> revealed Thursday that <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> recently found a buyer willing to pay $ 50 a share for his stake in the oil company, but he rejected the offer because it `` smacked of greenmail.'' <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Maneri </PERSON> said the claim `` is totally untrue and Mr. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> knows it.'' Furthermore, <PERSON> Maneri </PERSON> said that if a $ 50-a-share offer had surfaced, `` every indication we have is that <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> would have run through a brick wall to accept it.'' In recent months, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has been pressuring <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s management to take steps to raise the value of the company's stock, if necessary by breaking it up and selling off the pieces. He has backed up the demand by launching a proxy fight to install himself and four allies on <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s 14-seat board. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>, which emerged last month from a year under bankruptcy court protection, responded by restoring its $ 3 annual dividend and expanding its planned asset sales to $ 5 billion from $ 3 billion. Wednesday afternoon, company officials broke off three weeks of peace talks, claiming <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> was making unreasonable demands for special treatment in the financial restructuring. An <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> spokesman strongly denied the charge. A few hours later, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> released a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> containing his offer. He also said he would drop his threatened proxy contest if management would allow the other 211,000 stockholders to consider the offer at the company's annual meeting next month.
