<HEAD>Soybean Futures Finish Week On A High Note</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Soybean futures prices posted strong gains Friday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in anticipation of a dry Memorial Day weekend. Grain futures advanced slightly. On other markets, gold and silver retreated; livestock and meat futures were mixed; energy futures were mixed; and stock-index futures declined. Soybeans also were supported by indications the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had purchased soybean meal from both <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, analysts said. But weather concerns dominated the soybean and grain markets as they have throughout the unusually dry spring planting period. The nation's soybean stockpiles are declining and fears of tight supplies have pushed soybean futures prices to their highest levels in four years. Soybean prices declined on Wednesday and Thursday when rain entered the weekend weather forecasts. But Friday, most forecasters were calling for only scattered showers across the northern Plains and upper <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and dry conditions in the rest of the Corn Belt. `` The markets got hammered pretty good on Wednesday and Thursday,'' said <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Karlin </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` What we've pretty much done is moved to a level midway between Thursday's lows and Tuesday's highs.'' Soybean prices probably will open sharply higher Tuesday if the long weekend is as hot and dry as expected, analysts said. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> issued a six-to-10-day outlook after the close, predicting below-normal rainfall for most of the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> for the second half of next week. Wheat settled -LCB- cent lower to 3 \ cents higher with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.39 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 2 -LCB- cents to 7 cents higher with July at $ 2.16 -LCB- a bushel; oats were -RCB- cent to 1 -RCB- cents higher with July at $ 1.72 -RCB- a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to 16 -LCB- cents higher with July at $ 7.68 a bushel Gold and silver futures declined substantially on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in response to the dollar's gains against other major currencies and on expectations the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> was set to raise its discount interest rate, analysts said. Activity was extremely light as many traders got an early start on the weekend, said <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Raptoploulos </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The metals declined despite the inflationary effect of higher soybean prices, but Ms. <PERSON> Raptopoulos </PERSON> said it was not yet clear whether fears of inflation have finally left the metals markets. `` I would say today, perhaps, the inflationary fears diffused,'' she said. Gold settled $ 2.10 to $ 3.30 lower with June at $ 450.80 a troy ounce; silver was 8.4 cents to 8.5 cents lower with July at $ 6.575 a troy ounce. Cattle futures retreated on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as cash prices fell amid slackening wholesale demand. Retailers have reduced their beef purchases in anticipation of lower demand following the Memorial Day weekend, analysts said. Some traders, eyeing the recent runup in cattle prices, sold on fears of a repeat of the 1978 market