<HEAD>Griffin, Trump Sign Firm Agreement for Sale of Hotel-Casino
Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The on-again, off-again deal between <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> and <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> to split up hotel-casino operator Resorts International was officially sealed Friday, the millionaire entrepreneurs announced. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>, the TV talk-show host turned investor, will pay approximately $ 300 million for the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, company controlled by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> developer <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, the men said. Using his profits from the deal and other funds, <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> will buy back the company's unfinished crown jewel, the vast Taj Mahal casino in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, for $ 230 million. `` It looks like this is it,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON>'s brother and executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trump </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> `` We are pleased, as I think Mr. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> is pleased.'' The agreement, in contrast to a handshake deal that collapsed May 11 amid mutual recriminations, is definitive, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> said. The agreement calls for <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, Resorts' chairman, to get a total of $ 160 million _ $ 135 a share, or about $ 100 million, for his Class B shares, and $ 60 million to terminate his management contract. The Class B shares, which carry special voting rights, give him 88 percent control of the company. In addition, <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>, through <ORGANIZATION> Griffin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, agreed to pay approximately $ 200 million, or $ 36 a share, for all the company's common stock, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> said <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> agreed to pay $ 230 million for the <ORGANIZATION> Taj </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mahal </ORGANIZATION>, a grandiose project plagued by construction delays, and certain other assets. That purchase is subject to certain closing adjustments, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> first offered to buy Resorts on March 17 for $ 35 a share. After weeks of sparring, the men in April announced an agreement nearly identical to the one closed Friday, only to cancel it a month later, with <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> accusing <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> of failing to line up financing and <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> accusing <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> of seeking last-minute changes.
